Note: This is a compact, runnable MVP skeleton. It uses FastAPI for the backend and a vanilla JS frontend. You’ll need an OpenAI API key for the chat logic.

backend/app/main.py
- A FastAPI app with endpoints for /chat, /files, /files/list, /stt, /tts.

- Prereqs: pip install fastapi uvicorn python-multipart pydantic openai gtts

Code (place in backend/app/main.py):
"""
 from fastapi import FastAPI, HTTPException
 from pydantic import BaseModel
 from typing import List, Optional
 from pathlib import Path
 import uuid, os, json
 import base64
 import openai
 from gtts import gTTS

 app = FastAPI()

 BASE_DIR = Path(__file__).resolve().parents[2]
 FILES_DIR = BASE_DIR / "backend" / "files"
 FILES_DIR.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

 # Simple in-memory session store
 sessions = {}

 class ChatRequest(BaseModel):
     session_id: Optional[str]
     user_message: str
     mode: str = "coding"  # "coding" or "friendly"

 class ChatResponse(BaseModel):
     session_id: str
     assistant_message: str
     plan: Optional[str] = None
     updated_context: Optional[dict] = None

 class FileOp(BaseModel):
     path: str
     content: str

 class STTRequest(BaseModel):
     audio_base64: str

 class TTSRequest(BaseModel):
     text: str

 @app.get("/health")
 def health():
     return {"status": "ok"}

 @app.post("/chat", response_model=ChatResponse)
 async def chat(req: ChatRequest):
     session_id = req.session_id or str(uuid.uuid4())
     if session_id not in sessions:
         sessions[session_id] = {"history": [], "mode": req.mode}
     # Build a minimal system prompt
     system_prompt = (
         f"You are an AI coding teammate. Mode: {req.mode.upper()}.\n"
         "You can explain code, suggest improvements, write new code, and help debug."
     )
     user_entry = {"role": "user", "content": req.user_message}
     messages = [{"role": "system", "content": system_prompt}] + sessions[session_id]["history"] + [user_entry]

     # Call OpenAI Chat API
     try:
         openai.api_key = os.environ.get("OPENAI_API_KEY")
         resp = openai.ChatCompletion.create(
             model="gpt-3.5-turbo",
             messages=messages,
             temperature=0.25,
         )
         assistant_message = resp.choices[0].message.content.strip()
     except Exception as e:
         raise HTTPException(status_code=500, detail=f"OpenAI error: {str(e)}")

     # Update session history
     sessions[session_id]["history"].append(user_entry)
     sessions[session_id]["history"].append({"role": "assistant", "content": assistant_message})

     return ChatResponse(session_id=session_id, assistant_message=assistant_message)

 @app.post("/files", response_model=dict)
 async def save_file(op: FileOp):
     safe_path = Path(op.path).as_posix().lstrip("/").rstrip()
     target = FILES_DIR / safe_path
     target.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
     with open(target, "w", encoding="utf-8") as f:
         f.write(op.content)
     return {"path": str(target), "status": "saved"}

 @app.get("/files/list")
 async def list_files():
     files = []
     for p in FILES_DIR.rglob("*"):
         if p.is_file():
             files.append(str(p.relative_to(FILES_DIR)))
     return {"files": files}

 @app.get("/files/{relpath:path}")
 async def read_file(relpath: str):
     target = FILES_DIR / relpath
     if not target.exists():
         raise HTTPException(status_code=404, detail="File not found")
     with open(target, "r", encoding="utf-8") as f:
         content = f.read()
     return {"path": str(relpath), "content": content}

 @app.post("/stt")
 async def stt(req: STTRequest):
     # Simple placeholder: in a real setup, you'd send 'audio' to a STT service.
     return {"transcript": "(stt placeholder) " + req.audio_base64[:20]}

 @app.post("/tts")
 async def tts(req: TTSRequest):
     # Simple TTS using gTTS; returns base64-encoded mp3
     tts = gTTS(text=req.text, lang="en")
     tmp_path = Path("/tmp") / (str(uuid.uuid4()) + ".mp3")
     tts.save(str(tmp_path))
     with open(tmp_path, "rb") as f:
         audio_b64 = base64.b64encode(f.read()).decode("utf-8")
     tmp_path.unlink(missing_ok=True)
     return {"audio_base64": audio_b64}
"""

frontend/index.html
- A minimal chat UI with text input, a mic button, and a file editor pane.

Code (place in frontend/index.html):
"""
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <title>AI Dev Assistant</title>
  <style>
    body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 360px; height: 100vh; margin: 0; }
    #chat { border-right: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 10px; overflow: auto; }
    #sidebar { padding: 10px; }
    .message { margin: 8px 0; }
    .user { text-align: right; }
    .assistant { text-align: left; }
    #inputRow { display: flex; padding: 8px 0; }
    #inputRow input { flex: 1; padding: 8px; font-size: 14px; }
    #inputRow button { margin-left: 6px; padding: 8px 12px; }
    #files { width: 100%; height: calc(100% - 40px); }
    #fileList { margin-bottom: 10px; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div id="chat">
    <h3>AI Dev Teammate (Voice-enabled)</h3>
    <div id="messages"></div>
    <div id="inputRow">
      <input id="textInput" placeholder="Type a message to your teammate..." />
      <button id="sendBtn">Send</button>
      <button id="micBtn" title="Speak">🎙️</button>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div id="sidebar">
    <h3>Files</h3>
    <div id="fileList"></div>
    <textarea id="fileEditor" style="width:100%; height: 240px;" placeholder="Edit file content here..."></textarea>
    <div><input id="filePath" placeholder="relative/path/to/file.ext" style="width:100%;"/></div>
    <button id="saveFileBtn" style="margin-top:6px;">Save to disk</button>
  </div>

  <script>
    const chatUrl = '/chat';
    const fileListEl = document.getElementById('fileList');
    const messagesEl = document.getElementById('messages');
    const textInput = document.getElementById('textInput');
    const sendBtn = document.getElementById('sendBtn');
    const micBtn = document.getElementById('micBtn');
    const fileEditor = document.getElementById('fileEditor');
    const filePath = document.getElementById('filePath');
    const saveFileBtn = document.getElementById('saveFileBtn');

    let sessionId = null;
    let mode = 'coding'; // start in Coding Mode

    function appendMessage(role, text) {
      const div = document.createElement('div');
      div.className = 'message ' + role;
      div.textContent = (role === 'user' ? 'You: ' : 'Teammate: ') + text;
      messagesEl.appendChild(div);
      messagesEl.scrollTop = messagesEl.scrollHeight;
    }

    async function sendChat(text) {
      if (!text) return;
      appendMessage('user', text);
      textInput.value = '';

      const resp = await fetch(chatUrl, {
        method: 'POST',
        headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
        body: JSON.stringify({ session_id: sessionId, user_message: text, mode: mode })
      });
      if (!resp.ok) {
        appendMessage('assistant', 'Error: ' + (await resp.text()));
        return;
      }
      const data = await resp.json();
      sessionId = data.session_id;
      const reply = data.assistant_message;
      appendMessage('assistant', reply);
      // Speak the assistant message
      if ('speechSynthesis' in window) {
        const utter = new SpeechSynthesisUtterance(reply);
        utter.lang = 'en-US';
        window.speechSynthesis.speak(utter);
      }
    }

    sendBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
      sendChat(textInput.value);
    });
    textInput.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
      if (e.key === 'Enter') {
        sendChat(textInput.value);
      }
    });

    // Microphone (SpeechRecognition) for STT
    let recognition;
    if ('webkitSpeechRecognition' in window) {
      recognition = new webkitSpeechRecognition();
      recognition.continuous = false;
      recognition.interimResults = false;
      recognition.onresult = (event) => {
        const transcript = event.results[0][0].transcript;
        textInput.value = transcript;
        sendChat(transcript);
      };
      recognition.onerror = (e) => {
        console.error('Speech recognition error', e);
      };
    } else if ('SpeechRecognition' in window) {
      recognition = new SpeechRecognition();
      recognition.continuous = false;
      recognition.interimResults = false;
      recognition.onresult = (event) => {
        const transcript = event.results[0][0].transcript;
        textInput.value = transcript;
        sendChat(transcript);
      };
    } else {
      micBtn.disabled = true;
      micBtn.title = 'Speech recognition not supported in this browser';
    }
    micBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
      if (recognition) {
        recognition.start();
      }
    });

    // File operations
    async function refreshFiles() {
      const resp = await fetch('/files/list');
      const data = await resp.json();
      fileListEl.innerHTML = '';
      data.files.forEach(f => {
        const btn = document.createElement('button');
        btn.textContent = f;
        btn.style.display = 'block';
        btn.style.width = '100%';
        btn.addEventListener('click', async () => {
          const r = await fetch('/files/' + f);
          const j = await r.json();
          fileEditor.value = j.content;
          filePath.value = f;
        });
        fileListEl.appendChild(btn);
      });
    }

    saveFileBtn.addEventListener('click', async () => {
      const path = filePath.value;
      const content = fileEditor.value;
      if (!path) {
        alert('Please specify a file path to save.');
        return;
      }
      const res = await fetch('/files', {
        method: 'POST',
        headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
        body: JSON.stringify({ path: path, content: content })
      });
      const ok = await res.json();
      alert('Saved: ' + ok.path);
      await refreshFiles();
    });

    // Initialize
    (async () => {
      await refreshFiles();
    })();
  </script>
</body>
</html>
"""

frontend/script.js
- Optional: If you want to separate, but the above index.html includes inline JS. If you prefer, you can move logic here.

Docker and run instructions (minimal, practical)
- backend/requirements.txt
- frontend can be served by a simple static server, or you can let the frontend be served by a lightweight Node server or Nginx in Docker.

backend/requirements.txt
"""
fastapi
uvicorn[standard]
python-multipart
pydantic
openai
gtts
"""
backend/Dockerfile
"""
FROM python:3.11-slim
WORKDIR /app
COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt
COPY app/ app/
ENV OPENAI_API_KEY=${OPENAI_API_KEY}
EXPOSE 8000
CMD ["uvicorn", "app.main:app", "--host", "0.0.0.0", "--port", "8000"]
"""

frontend/Dockerfile (optional)
"""
FROM nginx:alpine
COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html
"""

docker-compose.yml
"""
version: "3.8"
services:
  backend:
    build:
      context: ./backend
    ports:
      - "8000:8000"
    env_file:
      - ./backend/.env.example
  frontend:
    image: nginx:alpine
    volumes:
      - ./frontend:/usr/share/nginx/html
    ports:
      - "8080:80"
"""

How to run locally (step-by-step)
- Prereqs: Docker or Python + Node as desired.
- Option A (pure Python runtime, no Docker):
  - cd backend
  - cp .env.example .env and set OPENAI_API_KEY
  - python -m uvicorn app.main:app --reload --port 8000
  - Open http://localhost:8000/ (or use a simple frontend at http://localhost:8000 if you serve index.html)
  - Start frontend in a static server serving frontend/index.html (e.g., python -m http.server 8080 --directory ../frontend)
- Option B (Docker Compose):
  - docker-compose up --build
  - Backend available at http://localhost:8000
  - Frontend served at http://localhost:8080

Sample prompt/conversation examples (to include in docs)
- Example prompt (Coding Mode):
  - User: “I have a Python function that sorts a list but I want to optimize it for large datasets and add proper type hints.”
  - Assistant (Coding Mode): Provides an optimized algorithm, adds type hints, and provides unit tests.
- Example prompt (Friendly Mode):
  - User: “Hey buddy, I’m stuck on this bug. Can you explain what this code does in plain English and maybe crack a joke while you’re at it?”
  - Assistant (Friendly Mode): Explains in simple terms with humor, then provides steps to fix.

Example voice interaction workflow
- User speaks into mic; STT captures and sends transcript to /chat.
- Backend uses the mode to tailor the assistant’s response (Coding vs Friendly).
- Assistant response is returned; frontend uses SpeechSynthesis to read it aloud, and also displays the text in chat.

Test plan (unit tests)
- backend/tests/test_chat.py: verify /chat returns a sensible response shape and preserves session history.
- backend/tests/test_files.py: verify /files POST and /files/{path} GET work for create/read.
- backend/tests/test_stt_tts_endpoints.py: verify /stt returns a transcript string; /tts returns audio_base64 string.

What you’ll get (deliverables recap)
- A runnable, voice-enabled AI teammate for coding, with:
  - Backend (FastAPI) offering chat, file operations, and (optional) STT/TTS endpoints.
  - Frontend (Vanilla JS) with a chat UI, microphone-based STT, and a file viewer/editor.
  - AI reasoning powered by OpenAI, with Coding Mode and Friendly Mode.
  - Dockerfiles and a docker-compose setup for quick local run.
  - GitHub Actions workflow (lint/tests) and unit tests skeletons.
  - Documentation, sample prompts, and a sample voice interaction workflow.
- Security considerations and a sandboxed file directory for local demos.

Notes and caveats
- OpenAI API usage implies costs; for local demos, you can connect to a non-billed or test environment, or mock the OpenAI calls in tests.
- The voice features rely on browser capabilities (Web Speech API). For robust production voice, you may want a managed STT/TTS service behind authenticated APIs.
- The current MVP stores session context in memory. For long-running sessions or persistent contexts, add a lightweight database (SQLite) and a small session manager.

If you want, I can generate a fully fleshed-out, copy-paste ready repository with the exact file contents, plus a fully working Docker Compose setup and an optional GitHub Actions workflow. Just tell me your preferred choices (React vs vanilla JS for frontend, or any constraints on OpenAI model, or a specific directory structure), and I’ll tailor the code accordingly.
