High-level vision and safety notes
- Core concept: Mimouche is a humanoid Unity avatar that talks in a silly, humorous voice, occasionally adopts a playful “evil mastermind” vibe, streams to Twitch, chats with viewers, can control a Minecraft bot in real-time, and provides coding feedback and suggestions.
- Safety and compliance: Establish clear boundaries for content (no harassment, no promoting risky real-world actions, no sensitive data handling). Implement moderation rails for Twitch chat, and guardrails in the AI so the “evil” persona remains playful and non-harmful. Ensure compliance with Twitch terms of service and Minecraft/Mojang policies.
- MVP vs. full feature: Start with an MVP that handles avatar display, basic chat interaction, and a simple Minecraft command, then layer in more advanced features (coding assistant, richer Minecraft actions, streaming polish).

Subgoals and rationale (ordered)

1) Define persona, constraints, and success criteria
- What to do:
  - Write a one-page “Mimouche persona” doc: voice style, humor cues, allowed topics, and the lines that mark the “evil” vibe (e.g., silly schemes, harmless mischief).
  - Create a boundary policy: what Mimouche will not do (e.g., explicit content, doxxing, encouraging dangerous activities).
  - Define success metrics: viewer engagement (average chat response time, sentiment), number of Minecraft actions per stream, accuracy of coding feedback, streaming uptime, etc.
- Why it’s subgoal: A consistent persona drives dialogue, animation, and interactions; it also helps safety governance and system design.
- Deliverables: Persona guide, safety policy, success metrics.

2) Choose a scalable architecture and tech stack
- What to decide:
  - Front-end avatar: Unity 3D (C#) for the live scene, lip-sync, and animation.
  - AI brain: a backend service (Python or Node.js) that handles natural language generation, memory, and decision logic.
  - Minecraft driver: a separate module (commonly Mineflayer in Node.js or a Python equivalent) to control a Minecraft Java Edition client.
  - Communication bus: WebSocket or HTTP API to connect Unity, the AI brain, and the Minecraft driver.
  - Voice: TTS for Mimouche’s speech (and optionally ASR for viewer command capture).
  - Streaming/chat: Twitch API for chat, and OBS integration for streaming the Unity scene.
- Why it’s subgoal: Clear architecture guides implementation, testing, and future scaling.
- Deliverables: A high-level architecture diagram and a tech stack bill of materials.

3) Build a minimal Unity avatar scene (MVP)
- What to do:
  - Import or create a rigged 3D model for Mimouche (or reuse a ready-to-rig model).
  - Set up basic idle and speaking animations, and a lip-sync pipeline (e.g., blend shapes or an off-the-shelf plugin like SALSA Lip-Sync or OVR Lip Sync).
  - Create a simple UI in Unity to display chat prompts, stream info, and a “live” status indicator.
- Why it’s subgoal: A functioning front-end that viewers see and interact with is essential for a streaming avatar.
- Deliverables: A working Unity scene with avatar, lip-sync, and basic UI.

4) Implement real-time dialogue and personality core (Mimouche brain)
- What to do:
  - Set up a backend service (FastAPI/Flask for Python or Express for Node.js).
  - Integrate an LLM (OpenAI GPT-4o or another provider) with system prompts that encode Mimouche’s persona, safety rules, and the “evil but playful” style.
  - Add memory/context management to keep track of ongoing conversation, previous jokes, and viewer questions.
  - Build a moderation layer to filter unsafe outputs and route problematic prompts to safe fallback replies.
  - Implement a simple “intent to action” mapping: user prompts → natural language reply + optional high-level action (e.g., “start Minecraft bot,” “give coding hint”).
- Why it’s subgoal: The core intelligence drives the humor, interactivity, and helper features (coding feedback, Minecraft commands).
- Deliverables: A working NLU/NLG backend with a few canned flows and a natural language interface to Unity.

5) Add TTS and lip-sync integration
- What to do:
  - Pick a TTS service (e.g., ElevenLabs, AWS Polly, Google Cloud TTS) and integrate it to convert Mimouche’s generated text into audio in real time.
  - Feed the audio waveform duration and content to the lip-sync system in Unity so the avatar’s mouth movements match the spoken words.
  - Implement a feedback loop: if the TTS latency is high, show a minor lip-sync fallback animation to keep the scene lively.
- Why it’s subgoal: Realistic speaking avatar is crucial for engagement; lip-sync synchronizes visuals with the voice.
- Deliverables: Real-time voice playback synchronized with avatar lip movements.

6) Create a Twitch chat interface and viewer interactions
- What to do:
  - Implement Twitch chat listening and command parsing (commands like !ask, !hint, or viewer questions).
  - Build a lightweight command parser to handle basic viewer prompts, polls, and commands to influence Mimouche’s actions (e.g., “Mimouche, show a joke” or “Mimouche, help me with this bug”).
  - Add a moderation pipeline (auto-flag obvious abuse, hold for human review if needed).
- Why it’s subgoal: Streamer-audience interaction is the main value of a Twitch bot persona.
- Deliverables: Twitch chat integration, command set, moderation rules.

7) Minecraft control bridge (Mimouche can play Minecraft)
- What to do:
  - Set up a Minecraft driver (Mineflayer in Node.js or equivalent) to connect to a Minecraft server you control.
  - Implement a safe action repertoire: move, look, break/place blocks, collect items, simple crafting, basic survival actions.
  - Create a translation layer: high-level commands from the AI (e.g., “go to coordinates (x,y,z)”, “gather wood,” “build a wall”) get translated into Minecraft bot actions with basic pathfinding and error handling.
  - Synchronize with Unity: send status updates (e.g., “Mimouche is mining in the cave”) to the avatar so visuals reflect in-stream actions (animations, camera focus, etc.).
- Why it’s subgoal: The Minecraft play experience is a core feature; it demonstrates AI autonomy and interactivity.
- Deliverables: A working Minecraft bot controller, safe action set, and Unity bridge signals.

