  - Integrate with the dialogue system so Mimouche can offer step-by-step suggestions, links to docs, and short example fixes.
  - Add a “live coding helper” mode where Mimouche can propose high-level design approaches or debug steps during viewer questions.
- Why it’s subgoal: A distinctive value-add that makes Mimouche feel like a capable teammate, not just a streamer.
- Deliverables: Coding feedback module, example prompts, and a test harness to validate feedback quality.

9) End-to-end streaming pipeline and OBS/Twitch integration
- What to do:
  - Ensure Unity scene rendering can be captured by OBS (or stream directly from Unity if you prefer).
  - Integrate viewer prompts and Twitch chat rendering into the on-stream UI (for example, showing the latest chat, prompts, or Misty “evil plan” lines).
  - Implement basic stream health checks (latency, frame rate, audio latency) and a fallback/auto-reconnect mechanism.
- Why it’s subgoal: A stable, polished stream experience is essential for audience retention.
- Deliverables: Working streaming pipeline with Unity-to-OBS integration and Twitch chat display.

10) Safety, testing, and quality assurance
- What to do:
  - Create test scripts for the dialogue system (edge cases, long conversations, conflicting intents).
  - Run staged tests with simulated chat and simulated Minecraft actions to verify timing and synchronization.
  - Establish a review process for content that may be flagged by viewers; implement a quick “pause and review” flow if needed.
- Why it’s subgoal: Early detection of edge cases reduces on-stream failures and improves viewer trust.
- Deliverables: Test suites, moderation rules, and a runbook for issues.

11) Iterative polish and feature expansion
- What to do:
  - Improve lip-sync quality, add more expressive gestures in Unity (head tilts, smiles, villains’ cackles).
  - Expand Minecraft capabilities (more complex tasks, simple automation sequences, event-based actions).
  - Add more coding assistance templates (common patterns, debugging strategies, and mini-tutorials).
  - Implement viewer-driven moments (polls, “challenge Mimouche” prompts, or “ask for help with X” events).
- Why it’s subgoal: Incremental improvements keep the project engaging and scalable.
- Deliverables: Expanded capabilities, improved UX, more robust interactions.

Optional architectural refinements and tips
- Decouple AI behavior from avatar rendering: keep the “brain” service stateless or with a short-term memory, and push state into Unity for visuals. This makes it easier to scale or replace components.
- Use a lightweight message bus: a central WebSocket or gRPC channel can help all modules communicate with low latency.
- Logging and telemetry: capture prompts, responses, Minecraft actions, and viewer interactions to iterate on persona and features.
- Local vs cloud: for latency-sensitive parts (speech, lip-sync), prefer local TTS or a latency-tolerant setup; for heavy LLM workloads, a cloud-based service is fine with local fallback.
- Privacy and consent: consider what data you log from chat and code snippets; provide viewers with a privacy note and an opt-out if needed.

Suggested phased timeline (rough)
- Phase 0 (Week 1): Define persona, success metrics, high-level architecture, safety boundaries.
- Phase 1 (Weeks 2-3): Develop MVP Unity avatar with lip-sync and basic chat UI; set up a basic backend for dialogue.
- Phase 2 (Weeks 4-5): Add Minecraft driver and bridge to Unity; implement simple viewer interactions and a few Minecraft actions.
- Phase 3 (Weeks 6-7): Implement TTS, full dialogue flow, and coding assistance basics.
- Phase 4 (Week 8+): Polish, add more complex Minecraft actions, improve streaming pipeline, run user tests and iterate.

What I can help you with next
- Draft detailed system design documents for each subsystem.
- Create a concrete task board with milestones, estimated effort, and risk flags.
- Provide example prompts and system messages to encode Mimouche’s personality safely.
- Suggest sample data schemas for chat logs, Minecraft actions, and coding feedback.
- Offer a minimal viable code skeleton (high-level pseudocode) for the Minecraft bridge and the Unity-frontend bridge.

If you want, I can tailor the plan to your preferred tech stack (e.g., Python-based backend with React frontend inside Unity, or a Node.js stack with Mineflayer) and give you a more exact task breakdown with estimated time per subtask.
