Great idea, and we can break it into clear, manageable subgoals. Below is a step-by-step decomposition that keeps the big-picture goals intact while giving concrete subgoals you can tackle one by one. I’ll treat the GPT-6-nano mention as a placeholder for a local/remote large language model API you’ll plug in, with an abstraction layer so you can swap models later without reworking everything.

High-level plan overview
- Goal modules:
  - Unity-based AI streamer avatar with lip-sync, voice, and chat behavior
  - Twitch/OBS streaming integration (via window capture / virtual camera)
  - Minecraft control interface driven by the AI (via safe remote-control mechanism)
  - AI coding assistant that can suggest and apply code improvements
  - Local web page that serves and displays code files and their changes
- Data flows: user input (voice/text) -> LLM -> avatar actions + speech -> streaming output; AI coding assistant can modify local files and update the web viewer
- Safety and scope: The AI should only access intentionally exposed resources (designated code directory, local server for web UI), require explicit user permission for edits, and avoid broad system access.

Step-by-step subgoals and reasoning

Subgoal 0 — Clarify scope, constraints, and success criteria
- Define the minimum viable product (MVP) vs. full feature set.
  - MVP: Unity window with AI-ready avatar, basic speech input/output, simple Twitch streaming via OBS, basic Minecraft control via RCON, and a simple local code-view web page.
  - Optional enhancements: full lip-sync, advanced Minecraft automation, more robust coding assistant features, offline/local model inference, better security safeguards.
- Decide model hosting approach for GPT-6-nano (or equivalent):
  - Cloud API (low latency, easier to update)
  - Local inference (greater privacy, more setup)
  - Hybrid (local for short prompts, cloud for longer ones)
- Define safety/privacy rules:
  - AI can only access a configured “code directory” for code viewing/editing.
  - User prompts must authorize code changes.
  - No arbitrary file system access beyond the designated folder.

Subgoal 1 — Architecture design and data flows
- Create a component map:
  - Unity UI/Avatar: 3D model, animations, lip-sync, voice capture
  - Voice/Chat: speech-to-text (STT), text-to-speech (TTS)
  - LLM Controller: a single interface to talk to GPT-6-nano (or chosen model), handles prompt management, context, and safety filters
  - Minecraft Controller: Responsible for sending safe commands to a running Minecraft server (via RCON or a controlled API)
  - AI Coding Assistant: analyzes code, suggests improvements, and can apply edits to a local repository
  - Web UI Server: serves a dynamic page showing code files and live changes
  - OBS/Twitch Bridge: ensures the Unity window can be captured by OBS and streamed to Twitch
- Data flow outline:
  - Player speaks or types → STT → LLM Controller processes prompt → avatar behavior and dialogue output (TTS for speaking) → streaming display
  - LLM may issue Minecraft commands or code edits → apply via Minecraft API or local file edits
  - Coding assistant updates local code and triggers the Web UI server to refresh
- Non-functional needs: performance targets (low-latency prompts), robust error handling, logging, and configurability for Twitch keys and server addresses.

Subgoal 2 — Unity project scaffolding and folder layout
- Create a Unity project with a stable version (LTS recommended, e.g., Unity 2021/2022).
- Folder structure to ensure “open folder and it works”:
  - Assets/
    - Scenes/
      - StreamingStudio.unity
    - AVATAR/
      - Models/ (avatar.fbx, blendshapes, animations)
      - LipSync/ (phoneme-based lip-sync assets)
      - AnimControllers/
    - AI/
      - LLMBridge/ (interfaces to the LLM)
      - STT/ (speech-to-text)
      - TTS/ (text-to-speech assets)
      - CodingAssistant/
      - Minecraft/
    - WebUI/
      - WebServer/ (local JSON/HTML endpoints)
      - CodeViewer/
    - OBSBridge/ (window capture hooks or metadata)
    - Utilities/ (config parsers, logging)
  - Plugins/External/ (ONNX, protobuf, etc., if needed)
  - ProjectSettings/
- Include a README with explicit setup steps: install Unity version, install any required plugins, place the code directory for the viewer, configure environment variables, and how to run the launcher.

Subgoal 3 — Avatar and scene setup in Unity
- Import a ready-to-use avatar (or a simple humanoid model) with:
  - Facial rig compatible with lip-sync (blendshapes or bones)
  - Basic idle and talking animations
- Implement lip-sync:
  - Use phoneme-driven lip-sync or approximate via amplitude of audio for optically believable mouth movement
- Implement avatar dialogue display:
  - Subtitles or a speech bubble to accompany voice
- Build a simple UI panel in Unity for:
  - Start/Stop streaming
  - Personalization options (name, persona)
- Ensure the Unity window runs in a resizable window mode for OBS capture

Subgoal 4 — STT and TTS integration
- Choose a STT provider (Cloud or local) and connect via a Unity plugin or C# wrapper.
- Choose a TTS provider to synthesize the avatar’s voice; ensure the output is streamed to the Unity audio output to match lip-sync.
- Implement a synchronized pipeline:
  - On user speech, STT returns text → display on screen → feed to LLM → LLM returns response → synthesize audio and animate lips to match.

Subgoal 5 — LLM integration layer (GPT-6-nano abstraction)
- Create an LLMBridge interface with:
  - SendPrompt(inputText, context) -> responseText
  - Manage context window (short-term memory for conversation)
  - Safety filters and role prompts (system prompts)
  - Ability to enqueue prompts and handle latency gracefully
- Implement a fallback and retry policy (timeouts, reconnection).
- Replaceable model backend:
  - Implement a plugin/adapter model that can swap GPT-6-nano with GPT-4, local Llama, or other APIs without changing the rest of the app.
- Tie LLM to avatar behavior:
  - Parse LLM response to derive actions: speak text, trigger Minecraft commands, or request code edits.

Subgoal 6 — Minecraft control interface
- Choose a safe control approach:
  - RCON (Remote Console) to a running Minecraft server for world-building commands
  - Or a local mod that exposes a lightweight API for commands (build, place block, toggle player, etc.)
- Implement a MinecraftController in Unity:
  - Authenticate to the server
  - Enqueue commands from LLM responses
  - Provide progress/status feedback in Unity (e.g., “Building: House”)
- Safety: implement a whitelist of allowed commands and a sandboxed domain to prevent abuse or destructive actions.

Subgoal 7 — AI coding assistant
- Define scope: code review, bug fix suggestions, refactoring recommendations, minor code enhancements.
- Implement a coding-assistant module that:
  - Monitors a configured code directory (read-only for viewing, write-enabled with explicit user consent)
  - Uses LLM to generate suggestions on changes
  - Applies changes via a controlled patch mechanism (diff + patch) or direct edits, gated by user approval prompts in Unity
- UI integration:
  - A panel showing file list, suggested changes, and a diff view
  - A “Apply changes” button with a confirmation step
- Security design:
  - Only edits within a specified code directory
  - Log all edits with timestamps and author information

Subgoal 8 — Web page to view code files and live changes
- Build a small local web server in C# (HttpListener) or use a lightweight framework (ASP.NET Core minimal API).
- Serve:
  - A dynamic HTML page displaying code files, folder tree, and diffs
  - A live refresh mechanism (WebSocket or polling) to reflect file changes
- Implement a simple viewer:
  - Directory browser
  - Code viewer with syntax highlighting (e.g., highlight.js)
  - A history/log of edits made by the AI assistant
- Security considerations:
  - Serve only the designated code directory
  - Disable arbitrary file access beyond the allowed path
  - Use simple authentication or a basic token if needed during development

Subgoal 9 — OBS/Twitch streaming setup
- OBS window capture:
  - Ensure Unity runs in windowed mode, exposed as a standard program window
  - In OBS, use Window Capture or Game Capture to grab the Unity window
- Twitch streaming setup:
  - Create/obtain a Twitch stream key
  - Configure OBS streaming settings (codec, bitrate, resolution, FPS)
  - Optional: add a static overlay or on-screen alerts
- Latency considerations:
  - Slightly adjust buffering to balance real-time feel with video/audio quality

Subgoal 10 — Project packaging and making it “open-folder-and-work”
- Ensure a single runnable launcher or simple script:
  - A launcher that:
    - Locates a configured Unity project folder
    - Opens it in Unity (preferred: provide an Editor script or a local build with instructions)
    - Starts a local web server for code viewing
- Provide a clear, minimal set of prerequisites:
  - Unity version
  - .NET version
  - Any required Python/Node components if used for STT/TTS or web server
- Include a detailed README with:
  - Step-by-step setup instructions
  - How to configure the LLM endpoint
  - How to configure Minecraft server/RCON
  - How to start OBS and Twitch streaming
  - How to customize the avatar persona and voice

Subgoal 11 — Safety, permissions, and testing plan
- Implement permission prompts for code edits
- Build a sandbox mode for Minecraft commands to prevent accidental damage
- Create a test suite outline:
  - LLM response sanity checks (relevant prompts, no dangerous actions)
  - Avatar lip-sync vs. audio quality tests
  - Web UI viewer correctness (directory listing and diffs)
  - OBS/streaming pipeline (window capture works reliably)
- Manual test steps for end-to-end flow:
  - Start Unity app, speak to it, verify LLM reply, avatar speaks, Minecraft actions executed, code viewer updates with edits

Subgoal 12 — Milestones and MVP plan
- MVP Milestone:
  - Unity scene with avatar, basic STT/TTS loop, LLM prompt cycle, simple OBS capture, a basic Minecraft command via RCON, and a minimal web viewer showing a single code file’s content
- Next Milestones (optional):
  - Lip-sync in sync with voice
  - Rich Minecraft interactions
  - Full coding assistant with patch application
  - Web UI supporting multiple files and diffs
  - Offline/local LLM inference capability

Subgoal 13 — Implementation schedule and deliverables
- Week 1: Scoping, architecture, repo setup, and Unity project skeleton
- Week 2: Avatar, lip-sync basics, STT/TTS integration, basic LLM bridge
- Week 3: Minecraft controller (RCON) and safe command set, code viewer scaffolding
- Week 4: AI coding assistant workflow, web server viewer, OBS/Twitch basics
- Week 5: End-to-end testing, polishing UI, packaging, and documentation
- Deliverables:
  - Unity project folder ready to open in Unity with a README and setup script
  - Local web server hosting code viewer
  - Simple Minecraft command demo
  - OBS-ready window setup instructions

Notes on feasibility and caveats
- GPT-6-nano is not a known public model as of my knowledge cutoff. Treat it as a placeholder for any LLM you actually deploy (GPT-4/turbo, Llama, etc.). The architecture above is model-agnostic thanks to the LLMBridge abstraction.
- Building an AI that can autonomously edit local code carries risk. Implement strict safeguards: guardrails, clear user consent, and a hard cap on what directories can be edited.
- Minecraft control via automated commands is feasible via RCON or a local mod API, but ensure you’re compliant with the game’s terms of service and any server policies.
- Ensure you respect Twitch/OBS terms of service and local privacy laws when streaming and recording.

