Below is a step-by-step breakdown of subgoals and concrete tasks you’ll need to complete to make the Unity-based AI Twitch streamer project run out-of-the-box in Unity 2022.3 LTS with .NET 4.x compatibility. Each subgoal includes rationale, concrete tasks, and acceptance criteria. I’ve organized them so you can implement, test, and iterate module-by-module.

High-level architecture recap (why these pieces exist)
- Scene and avatar: A live streamer avatar with lip-sync/expressions, controllable in real-time.
- AI integration: A CodingAssistant and an LLMBridge that call an AI API (e.g., OpenAI) asynchronously to generate prompts, responses, and actions.
- OBS integration: A bridge to OBS WebSocket to switch scenes and toggle streaming from Unity.
- Audio: TTS to speak AI responses and STT to capture mic input for prompts or chat-to-speech.
- UI: Live chat overlay, AI controls, TTS/STT controls, streaming status, and a log panel for debugging.
- Robustness: Centralized error handling, UI-driven testing, and build-compatibility safeguards (Windows standalone; WebGL/WebGL-disable paths).

Subgoal 1 — Project setup and compatibility
What you’ll do and why:
- Ensure the project uses Unity 2022.3 LTS and .NET 4.x compatibility so all libraries (OBS WebSocket, OpenAI HTTP, System.Speech, etc.) work as expected.
- Prepare a clean, repeatable project structure (Assets, Plugins, Scenes, Scripts, UI, Logs).

Tasks:
- Create or open a Unity 2022.3 LTS project.
- Set API Compatibility Level to .NET 4.x (Edit > Project Settings > Player > Other Settings > Configuration > Api Compatibility Level).
- Create a canonical folder structure if not present:
  - Assets/Scenes/Streamer.unity
  - Assets/Scripts/
  - Assets/UI/
  - Assets/Plugins/ (for OBS WebSocket client libraries and any native plugins)
  - Assets/Resources/ (for configuration assets and audio clips)
  - ProjectSettings/ (provide a compatible set of ProjectSettings files)
- Import required plugins and packages:
  - OBS WebSocket client for Unity (see Notes below for package name and source).
  - A WebSocket library suitable for Unity (e.g., NativeWebSocket or WebSocketSharp, chosen based on compatibility).
  - Newtonsoft.Json (if not included by default, for robust JSON handling).
  - Optional: a microservice stub or local server for AI if you don’t want to hit the public API directly from Unity during testing.
- Create a basic scene setup with a placeholder avatar (see Subgoal 2) to verify compilation.

Acceptance criteria:
- Project opens without compile errors in a fresh Unity 2022.3 LTS session.
- Api Compatibility Level is .NET 4.x.
- OBS WebSocket libraries and WebSocket libraries are present in Assets/Plugins and compile without errors.

Subgoal 2 — Scenes & GameObjects: main scene and avatar
What you’ll do and why:
- A single main scene Streamer.unity holds the entire runtime flow and UI.
- An avatar GameObject with an AvatarController implements basic movement, lip-sync readiness, expressions, and face tracking hooks.

Tasks:
- Create Assets/Scenes/Streamer.unity as the main scene.
- Create a root GameObject StreamerRoot with a child:
  - Avatar (prefab or Scene instance) with an AvatarController script attached.
  - Optional: A lip-sync helper or blendshape controller (e.g., BlendShapes on a SkinnedMeshRenderer) wired to phoneme timing.
- Create a UI Canvas with:
  - LiveChatOverlay panel (online chat messages).
  - AIControls panel (buttons to trigger prompts, input field to send prompts).
  - TTS/STT controls panel (buttons to start/stop TTS and to begin STT recording).
  - StreamingStatus panel (indicates OBS state: connected, streaming, scene, etc.).
  - A generic LogPanel region to display runtime logs (or a dedicated LogPanel script that feeds UI).
- Create a simple EventSystem and CanvasScaler to ensure UI scales properly on different resolutions.

Acceptance criteria:
- Scene loads, Avatar appears in the scene, and basic UI panels render without errors.
- AvatarController script is attached and compiles (even if methods are placeholders initially).
- UI panels have functional buttons wired to placeholder or stub methods.

Subgoal 3 — OBS Integration: OBS WebSocket bridge
What you’ll do and why:
- You need to connect to OBS WebSocket to toggle streaming, switch scenes, and optionally respond to events (state changes, scene transitions).

Tasks:
- Integrate an OBS WebSocket client library into Assets/Plugins (choose either a Unity-friendly OBSWebsocket fork or a .NET standard client compatible with Unity; ensure it targets .NET 4.x).
- Implement OBSBridge (Assets/Scripts/OBSBridge.cs) with:
  - Connect(string host, int port, string password) and Disconnect().
  - async Task<bool> ConnectAsync() and a per-frame or event-based message loop.
  - Methods to:
    - StartStreaming/StopStreaming
    - SetScene(string sceneName)
    - GetCurrentScene and a way to subscribe to OBS events (e.g., on SceneChanged).
  - Basic error handling: retry logic, timeouts, and a status property (OBSStatus).
- Ensure OBS is configured with WebSocket server enabled (settings in OBS: Tools > WebSocket Server Settings > Enable WebSockets; set port default 4455 and a password if you choose).
- Wire OBSBridge to UI: a toggle button to start/stop streaming and a dropdown to switch scenes (optional for demonstration).

Notes:
- OBS WebSocket v4/v5 changes API; pick a Unity-friendly wrapper and adjust calls accordingly. If you use OBSWebSocket-DotNet or a Unity-compatible fork, follow its example usage.
- For testing, you can add a simple mock OBSBridge in case OBS is not running, to allow compilation and UI testing.

Acceptance criteria:
- Unity can connect to OBS WebSocket, start/stop streaming, and switch scenes via code.
- OBSBridge compiles and runs without exceptions in the Unity console (when OBS is available or when mocked).
- UI shows current OBS state or logs status changes.

Subgoal 4 — AI integration: CodingAssistant and LLMBridge
What you’ll do and why:
- Wire up AI components to produce live AI-driven prompts/responses. Use async networking to avoid blocking the main thread.

Tasks:
- Create LLMBridge (Assets/Scripts/LLMBridge.cs) with:
  - API endpoint configuration (e.g., OpenAI Chat Completions or Completion API).
  - async Task<string> SendPromptAsync(string prompt) that posts JSON payload and awaits response.
  - Handling authentication (API key) securely (prefer external configuration; avoid hard-coding in source).
  - Basic rate-limiting and retry logic with exponential backoff.
- Create CodingAssistant (Assets/Scripts/CodingAssistant.cs) that:
  - Builds prompts for coding tasks or streamer prompts (e.g., generate a witty line, craft a Twitch chat response, generate an OBS scene switch script).
  - Calls LLMBridge.SendPromptAsync and parses the AI results.
  - Returns structured results: text response, and optionally a list of actions (e.g., "switch to scene 'BRB'").
- Create an AIUIController (Assets/Scripts/AIUIController.cs) to:
  - Expose UI actions: TriggerPrompt(), ShowAIResponse(string), and a live display panel for AI responses.
  - Coordinate between user input field (PromptInput) and AI results.
- Ensure async flows:
  - Use Unity's Task-based async (async/await) with proper synchronization to Unity main thread for UI updates (e.g., using UnityMainThreadDispatcher or a small wrapper to marshal back to Unity thread). If you don’t have a dispatcher, use Unity's coroutine wrappers around Task results via TaskCompletionSource or simply use Unity’s async-friendly patterns.
- UI wiring:
  - Wire a Prompt button to call TriggerPrompt() to assemble a prompt, send to LLMBridge, and display results in the AI response panel in real time.
  - Continuously display AI responses as they come (streaming responses can be simulated or implemented if the API supports streaming).

Notes:
- For testing without network, you can implement a mock LLMBridge that returns canned responses; later replace with OpenAI or other provider.
- If using OpenAI, ensure you respect rate limits and provide a safe-guard to avoid exposing API keys in builds.

Acceptance criteria:
- AI calls are asynchronous and do not freeze the main thread.
- AI responses render in the UI (live update if streaming or incremental).
- There is a functional path from user input to AI output, via LLMBridge and CodingAssistant.

Subgoal 5 — Audio: TTS and STT
What you’ll do and why:
- TTS (text-to-speech) to vocalize AI responses.
- STT (speech-to-text) to capture mic input for prompts or chat-to-speech interactions.

Tasks:
- TTSController (Assets/Scripts/TTSController.cs):
  - Implement PlayText(string text) that turns text into audio and plays via an AudioSource.
  - Choose a backend:
    - Windows: System.Speech.Synthesis (via .NET) if supported by Unity on your target platform.
    - Cross-platform: a plugin-based TTS (e.g., Microsoft Cognitive Services TTS, Google Cloud TTS) or a local offline TTS engine if you want offline operation.
  - Ensure AudioClip generation from synthesized audio; attach to an AudioSource component and play.
  - Handle concurrency: prevent overlapping speech by queueing or canceling current playback.
- STTController (Assets/Scripts/STTController.cs):
  - StartRecording() to allocate microphone input and capture audio.
  - StopRecording() to finalize and convert to text locally or send to a cloud STT service (e.g., Google/STT, Azure Speech, or a local recognizer).
  - Return transcription via callback or Task<string>.
  - Enable basic error handling for microphone permission issues.
- Audio package requirements:
  - If System.Speech is not available in Unity across all platforms, provide a fallback: an external TTS/Speech service or a plugin. Document platform caveats (Windows best fit for System.Speech).
- UI wiring:
  - Bind TTS button to TTSController.PlayText(aiResponseText).
  - Bind STT Start/Stop to STTController and feed transcriptions back to the AI input box or chat overlay.

Security and privacy:
- Do not ship API keys in the Unity project; use a secure config (e.g., a local config file read at runtime, or a simple in-editor UI to input keys for testing). For production, route calls through a backend proxy or a secure key vault.

Acceptance criteria:
- TTS plays AI responses smoothly through an AudioSource.
- STT microphone input captures audio and returns transcription without crashing.
- Audio components compile and run on Windows standalone builds.

Subgoal 6 — UI design: live chat, AI prompts, and status
What you’ll do and why:
- A usable UI is essential for streaming: chat overlay, prompt controls, AI response display, and streaming status.

Tasks:
- Implement a LiveChatOverlay panel:
  - A scrollable area that appends chat messages (incoming Twitch chat or local chat simulation).
  - A small input field to simulate sending a chat message or to forward prompts to AI.
- Implement AIControls panel:
  - A text input for manual prompts to AI (PromptInput).
  - A Button to TriggerPrompt() and a panel to display AI responses live (AIResponsePanel).
- Implement TTS/STT controls:
  - Buttons: StartSTT, StopSTT, PlayAIResponse (or automatically play after AI response).
- Implement StreamingStatusPanel:
  - Text fields showing OBS connection status, streaming state, current scene, and a small indicator (green/yellow/red).
- Implement a unified LogPanel:
  - A scrolling text area that appends logs (Info, Warning, Error) from a central logging system.
  - Expose a public method to AppendLog(string message, LogType type) and connect Unity’s Debug.Log, Debug.LogError, Debug.LogWarning to this panel.
- Wiring:
  - Connect LiveChatOverlay to a simulated chat feed or a Twitch chat API (optional for out-of-box; a mock is acceptable for initial run).
  - Connect AIControls to AIUIController prompts.
  - Bind StreamingStatusPanel to OBSBridge status (e.g., OBSBridge.OnStatusChanged).

Acceptance criteria:
- All UI panels render without errors.
- Buttons and inputs perform the expected actions and display results in real-time.
- The LogPanel captures runtime errors and shows them in the UI.

Subgoal 7 — Real-time logging and error handling
What you’ll do and why:
- A robust in-Unity error-reporting system helps debugging during live streaming.

Tasks:
- Implement a global Logger (Assets/Scripts/Logger.cs) that:
  - Exposes static methods: LogInfo, LogWarning, LogError, and LogException.
  - Keeps a bounded internal buffer (e.g., last 500 messages) to avoid memory bloat.
  - Notifies LogPanel UI to display messages in real time.
- Refactor existing code to route messages through Logger instead of Debug.Log where appropriate.
- Ensure that exceptions in asynchronous tasks (AI calls, OBS calls, audio) are caught and surfaced to the UI (LogPanel) and to a fail-safe fallback (e.g., disable streaming gracefully and show an error banner).
- Add try-catch blocks around external calls (HTTP requests, WebSocket calls, mic APIs).

Acceptance criteria:
- No silent exceptions; all errors propagate to the LogPanel.
- The Unity Console remains free of uncaught exceptions on first open.
- User can see errors in the UI during streaming for quick debugging.

Subgoal 8 — Build compatibility and platform considerations
What you’ll do and why:
- The project should run as a standalone Windows build and be safe for other platforms as an optional extension.

Tasks:
- Windows Standalone build settings:
  - Ensure Windows platform selected in Build Settings.
  - Configure Scripting Backend to IL2CPP or Mono as appropriate for Unity 2022.3 (Mono is typical; IL2CPP can be used if needed).
  - Ensure Internet access permissions for AI calls and OBS WebSocket calls.
- WebGL/Web platforms:
  - If you ever build for WebGL, ensure incompatible APIs are excluded via preprocessor directives.
  - Disable unsupported APIs in WebGL builds (examples: HttpListener, System.Net.Http depending on platform). Use preprocessor directives:
    - #if UNITY_WEBGL
        // disable or stub out
      #endif
- Networking:
  - For Windows standalone, ensure firewall prompts or port openings for OBS WebSocket (4455 by default) and your local AI HTTP calls.
- Dependencies:
  - Confirm that all platform-specific libraries (e.g., System.Speech) are wrapped with #if UNITY_STANDALONE_WIN guards to avoid build failures on other platforms.

Acceptance criteria:
- A clean Windows standalone build can be created and runs without runtime errors.
- WebGL or other platform builds fail gracefully or have stubs (if you decide to support them later).

Subgoal 9 — Testing plan and validation
What you’ll do and why:
- A structured plan ensures you can verify the project works out-of-the-box and that all critical integrations function.

Tasks:
- Compile-time checks:
  - Ensure there are no compile errors after implementing AvatarController, AI integration, OBSBridge, and UI wiring.
- Runtime checks:
  - Launch Unity, load Streamer.unity, confirm UI elements render, the avatar appears, and the OBSBridge can connect (and handle no-OBS-state gracefully if OBS isn’t running).
  - Press the OBS “Connect” button; verify the OBS status indicator updates and that you can toggle streaming and switch scenes (if scenes exist).
  - Test AI: Trigger a prompt and confirm a response is displayed in AIResponsePanel. If using a mock, ensure the mock returns deterministic responses; if using OpenAI, ensure the API key is correctly configured via a secure config.
  - Test TTS: After AI response, press Play TTS and confirm audio plays. Test STT by starting recording, speaking into the mic, and confirming the transcription is shown or sent to AI.
  - Test UI log panel: generate log messages by performing actions and check they appear in the log UI.
- Error handling sanity:
  - Force a failure path (e.g., disconnect OBS mid-scene, network failure for AI) and verify the UI shows a clear error and remains responsive.

Acceptance criteria:
- All engineered paths work without crashes.
- The UI logs errors in the LogPanel and the Unity Console mirrors the same messages.
- The workflow from prompting the AI to hearing the AI response via TTS works in a streaming-ready loop.

Subgoal 10 — Placeholder replacement and “real implementations”
What you’ll do and why:
- Replace all placeholder methods with real implementations or robust mocks that behave like real systems during testing.

Tasks:
- Review all placeholder methods across AvatarController, OBSBridge, LLMBridge, CodingAssistant, TTSController, STTController, and UI controllers.
- Replace with functional code as described in prior subgoals (e.g., actual connect logic, actual prompts, actual audio playback).
- Ensure each interaction path has a small unit-test-like validation path (even in the editor) to verify connectivity or basic behavior.
- Remove any hard-coded strings that could cause drift and centralize constants in a single configuration object (e.g., Config.cs or ScriptableObject-based config).

Acceptance criteria:
- No placeholder methods remain; all public methods have a working implementation or a well-documented stub with a meaningful failure mode.
- The project behaves predictably in editor play mode.

What to deliver as part of the plan (summary checklist)
- ProjectSettings and Unity version compatibility:
  - Unity 2022.3 LTS, .NET 4.x API Compatibility Level.
  - ProjectSettings folder added or recreated to match 2022.3 expectations.
- Scenes & GameObjects:
  - Assets/Scenes/Streamer.unity created with:
    - Avatar GameObject with AvatarController attached.
    - UI canvases/panels for chat, AI controls, TTS/STT, and streaming status.
- OBS integration:
  - OBSBridge.cs (OBS WebSocket client) in Assets/Scripts/, wired to UI.
  - Plugins/OBS WebSocket client library present in Assets/Plugins/.
- AI integration:
  - LLMBridge.cs for OpenAI or chosen provider.
  - CodingAssistant.cs and AIUIController.cs to manage prompts and display results.
- Audio:
  - TTSController.cs and STTController.cs with a working audio pipeline (Windows-focused or plugin-based).
- UI:
  - LiveChatOverlay, AIControls, TTS/STT controls, streaming status panels.
  - LogPanel that displays runtime logs.
- Testing & logs:
  - Logger.cs hooking into UI and Unity’s debug logging for easy debugging.
- Build:
  - Windows standalone build path confirmed; WebGL paths guarded with preprocessor directives where applicable.

Acceptance criteria for “out-of-the-box” readiness
- The project opens cleanly in Unity 2022.3 LTS with no compile errors.
- Scene loads Streamer.unity, avatar appears, and UI panels render.
- OBSBridge can connect to OBS WebSocket server and toggle streaming/scenes (or provide a clean mock for testing).
- LLMBridge and CodingAssistant can send a prompt and display a response in the UI (or use a mock if API keys are not configured).
- TTS plays AI responses; STT captures microphone input and returns text.
- Logs appear in the UI LogPanel; errors surface in the UI and the Unity Console.
- A Windows standalone build can be produced and runs without runtime failures.
- In WebGL builds, unsupported APIs are disabled or guarded to avoid compilation/runtime errors.

Notes and practical tips
- OBS WebSocket integration requires that OBS is running and WebSocket server is enabled. Test with a basic script that calls StartStreaming and SetScene.
- AI integration (OpenAI or similar) requires an API key. Use a secure approach to load keys in-editor (e.g., a ScriptableObject with a field for the key) and avoid committing keys in version control. For distribution, route calls through a backend you control or rely on a Unity-friendly OpenAI SDK if available.
- If you hit Unity or platform-specific limitations for System.Speech, implement a cross-platform fallback (e.g., a cloud TTS/STT service or a Unity plugin) and clearly document platform caveats.
- Keep the code well-organized with interfaces (e.g., IOBSBridge, ILLMBridge) to enable easy mocking for tests and to allow future replacement of underlying services.
- Provide a compact README with build steps, OBS config, and how to run the project locally (including how to start/stop streaming, how to input API keys, and how to test AI responses).

If you want, I can provide concrete starter code skeletons for key classes (AvatarController, OBSBridge, LLMBridge, CodingAssistant, TTSController, STTController, Logger, and UI controllers) and a minimal wiring diagram to copy into your project. I can also generate a minimal Unity package manifest and a sample configuration file layout to help you bring the project from plan to a runnable out-of-the-box state.
