What to use (easy-to-work-with tech stack)
- Unity (C#) for the avatar and real-time visuals.
- Python (3.x) for AI back-end, with a lightweight framework like FastAPI or Flask to expose HTTP endpoints.
- AI model options:
  - Use GPT-4-turbo or GPT-3.5-turbo via OpenAI API as a drop-in for “GPT-like” behavior.
  - If you have access to a smaller local model (e.g., a hypothetical GPT-5-nano or a smaller LLM), design the API to support switching models with minimal changes.
- OCR:
  - EasyOCR or Tesseract (Python). Prefer EasyOCR for simpler setup.
- Screen capture:
  - Windows: use Windows.Graphics.Capture or a safe, opt-in approach via a UI toggle. Provide a per-window capture to respect privacy.
- Streaming:
  - Twitch API for chat and commands (OAuth-based; use a library like TwitchLib for C# or a Python equivalent).
  - OBS integration: use NDI or a local plugin to share the Unity output as a scene; or rely on standard screen capture/scene composition in OBS.
- Audio:
  - TTS: use a cloud TTS service or a local TTS solution to generate voice for the avatar.
  - Lip-sync: drive mouth shapes from audio or from phoneme timing if you have a phoneme predictor.

Phased plan with concrete milestones
- Phase 1 (2–4 weeks): MVP avatar, lip-sync, and chat-based AI
  - Implement AvatarPrefab in Unity with basic expressions.
  - Add LipSync and a basic expression mapping to mood.
  - Build a simple AIBackendClient and PromptManager; hook Unity to display AI replies as speech and on-screen text.
  - Add Twitch chat read/write (mock channel or a test channel).
- Phase 2 (2–4 weeks): Perception and memory
  - Implement MemoryManager and persona prompts; refine the UI for mood changes.
  - Add ScreenObserver (opt-in) and OCRProcessor to extract screen text for use in replies.
  - Implement a basic CodeUnderstanding module that detects code blocks and explains them lightly.
- Phase 3 (2–4 weeks): Advanced animation and streaming integration
  - Fine-tune emotion-to-animation mapping; add more expressions and subtle eye movement.
  - Integrate OBS/NDI workflow; ensure Unity output is visible on stream with overlays for chat status.
  - Add moderation, safety filters, and a robust testing plan.
- Phase 4 (ongoing): Polish, testing, and deployment
  - Re-run integration tests, performance profiling, and user acceptance testing.
  - Prepare build packages and documentation; finalize the build-summary and readme.

Important caveats and guidance
- Impersonation concerns: If you intend to emulate the personality or branding of a real person, obtain explicit permission. Prefer an original, fictional VTuber persona to avoid rights issues.
- Privacy and consent: Screen-reading features must be opt-in with clear UI. Do not capture arbitrary windows or content without user consent.
- Hardware and latency: Real-time lip-sync and AI responses require careful performance tuning. Expect some latency; plan for a fallback (short responses) if the AI backend is slow.
- Licensing and assets: Use assets (3D models, textures, voice assets) you have rights to or create them yourself. Document licenses in the repo.
- Security: Protect API keys and tokens; load them from environment variables or config files excluded from source control.
- Realistic scope: Keep expectations aligned with MVP; use a staged approach to reduce risk.

