Great idea. Here’s a structured, step-by-step breakdown of logical subgoals you’d tackle to carry out “rewrite the files over again fully.” I’ll treat this as a full rewrite of a codebase or project files, with options to preserve the public API or to redesign it. If you want me to tailor this to a specific language, framework, or project, tell me and I’ll adjust.

Overall approach you’ll likely choose between:
- API-preserving rewrite: keep public interfaces the same, rewrite internals to be cleaner, faster, more maintainable.
- API-breaking rewrite: redesign interfaces, rename/fix modules, require migration steps for users.

Subgoal 1: Define objective and acceptance criteria
- What to do: Clarify what “fully rewritten” means for this project.
- What to decide and produce:
  - Scope: which files/modules are included; any files excluded.
  - API compatibility: preserve, version, or deprecate public APIs?
  - Quality targets: test coverage thresholds, performance goals, security checks, accessibility, etc.
  - Deliverables: new codebase structure, updated docs, migration guide if needed.
  - Acceptance criteria: a concrete checklist (e.g., all unit tests pass, linting passes, new architecture diagram present).
- Why it matters: aligns team, reduces rework, and provides a yardstick for progress.

Subgoal 2: Inventory and map existing files
- What to do: Create a complete inventory of all files, modules, assets, tests, and their relationships.
- Outputs:
  - List of all source files, test files, configuration files, data files, scripts.
  - Dependency graph: which modules depend on which.
  - Entry points and build targets.
  - Current pain points and hotspots (from issue tracker or metrics).
- Why it matters: you can’t rewrite what you don’t know; helps plan scope and risk.

Subgoal 3: Baseline assessment
- What to do: Establish a performance, correctness, and quality baseline.
- Actions:
  - Run existing test suite; capture coverage and flaky tests.
  - Run benchmarks or profiling to identify bottlenecks.
  - Note recurring bugs, tight coupling, and architectural smells.
- Outputs:
  - Baseline metrics (test pass rate, coverage, runtime, memory, lint issues).
  - List of risks and areas to focus on during rewrite.
- Why it matters: informs design decisions and helps measure progress later.

Subgoal 4: Architectural and design decisions
- What to do: Decide how you’ll structure the rewrite and what constraints to follow.
- Key decisions to document:
  - Architecture style: monolith vs modular, micro-frontend, library design, plugin points.
  - Language/version choices: keep current tech or upgrade (e.g., Python 3.11+, TS/JS version, dependencies).
  - Public API strategy: compatibility layer, deprecation plan, versioning approach.
  - Module boundaries and interfaces: define stable contracts, data models, error handling.
  - Coding standards: naming, testing, documentation, and lint rules.
- Why it matters: reduces rework and ensures consistency across the rewrite.

Subgoal 5: Choose rewrite approach and draft a roadmap
- What to do: Decide between incremental rewrite vs full rewrite in one go, and outline milestones.
- Options:
  - Incremental: rewrite modules one by one with tests/smoke checks, keep old code as compatibility layer.
  - Big-bang: complete rewrite in a single branch/release with a migration plan.
- Outputs:
  - Selected approach and rationale.
  - High-level roadmap with milestones, deliverables, and risk notes.
- Why it matters: affects risk, deployment, and time-to-value.

Subgoal 6: tooling, environment, and process setup
- What to do: Prepare the technical environment to support a rewrite.
- Tasks:
  - Version control strategy (branching model, PR process).
  - CI/CD setup for automated tests, linters, and builds.
  - Testing framework setup or upgrade; code quality tools (linters, type checks, static analyzers).
  - Documentation tooling (docs site, API docs generation).
