[2025-08-11 14:08:30] [INFO] 🧩 Chained reasoning:
I can’t help replicate a real person’s voice or persona. I can, however, help you design an original AI Twitch streamer with Unity 3D avatar, Discord/Twitch integration, lip-sync, emotions, multilingual speech, and memory. Below is a step-by-step breakdown of subgoals and what needs to be done at each step. It’s organized to give you a valid plan you could follow to create a Unity-based avatar and the supporting AI/streaming pipeline.

Big picture plan and guiding principles
- Create an original streamer persona (name, backstory, goals, tone) that is not copying any real person.
- Build a real-time pipeline: Twitch chat + Discord input → AI planning and response → speech synthesis with emotion → mouth/face animation → audience feedback (chat, subs, counts) → streaming overlay.
- Use Unity for the 3D avatar and lip-sync/expressions; use standard AI/ML APIs for language understanding and generation; use TTS for voice with controllable emotion; integrate with Discord and Twitch via bots.
- Scope controls: MVP first (basic avatar with lip-sync and simple responses), then iterate with memory, emotion depth, multi-language support, and streaming-time features (OBS timers, subscriber-based delays, etc.).

Subgoal 1: Define scope, constraints, and originality
What to do
- Create an original streamer persona concept: name (e.g., NovaEcho or VelvetCircuit), backstory, purpose (teach life lessons, entertain, light role-play), tone (playful, wise, a bit quirky), and language policy (English + French).
- Enumerate features you will not imitate (no cloning real people's voices or appearances).
- List non-functional requirements: real-time latency targets, accuracy of lip-sync, memory durability, data privacy, platform compatibility (Discord, Twitch, OBS, Unity).
Why this matters
- Prevents moral/ethical pitfalls and provides a clear boundary for development and content.
How to verify
- A one-page design document approved by the team outlining persona, language, and feature list.

Subgoal 2: Choose a safe, original avatar and animation plan
What to do
- Design an original 3D avatar concept (face, body, clothing) with a rig suitable for facial expressions and lip-sync.
- Plan blendshapes/morph targets for mouth shapes (visemes) and key emotional expressions (happy, surprised, angry, sad, thoughtful, etc.).
- Decide on a neutral to expressive eye gaze behavior and head tilt logic to feel “alive.”
- Decide on the animation pipeline (FBX import, blendshape-driven lips, animation clips for idle, talking, reacting).
Why this matters
- A convincing, responsive avatar depends on a clean rig and a robust viseme/emotion system.
How to verify
- A Unity prototype scene that shows a basic avatar with lip-sync driven by audio and a few facial expressions driven by AI state.

Subgoal 3: Set up Unity project structure and MVP avatar scene
What to do
- Create a Unity project with a clean folder structure:
  - Assets/Models (avatar and props)
  - Assets/Animations (idle, talking, expressions)
  - Assets/Materials
  - Assets/Scripts (AI interfacing, lip-sync, emotion controller)
  - Scenes/MainScene (avatar scene with UI for testing)
  - Plugins/Integrations (Discord/Twitch SDKs)
  - Audio and Localization assets
- Build an MVP scene: camera, lighting, avatar, basic UI, and a lip-sync component wired to an audio source.
- Implement a simple emotion controller that maps AI state to facial expressions and blendshape weights.
Why this matters
- A valid Unity project layout helps collaboration and future expansion; MVP helps you verify core visuals early.
How to verify
- Open Unity, import the MVP scene, and see a talking avatar with basic lip-sync and expressions.

Subgoal 4: Implement lip-sync and facial animation pipeline
What to do
- Implement a lip-sync system that maps audio (text-to-speech output) to viseme blendshapes.
- If possible, reuse existing Unity assets or plugins for viseme mapping (Mouth shapes for A, E, I, O, U, etc.).
- Tie facial expressions to a small state machine (emotion → blendshape targets).
- Ensure timing alignment between spoken words and mouth movements (minimize lag).
Why this matters
- Realistic lip-sync is critical for perceived naturalness in a talking avatar.
How to verify
- Generate a sample line, synthesize speech, and observe mouth animation matching phonemes in real time.

Subgoal 5: Design the AI back-end: memory, planning, and policy
What to do
- Choose an AI model for language understanding/generation (e.g., a current API-based model like GPT-4/4-turbo or other available LLMs). If you want a lighter setup, a single-purpose smaller model can handle planning with external tools.
- Create a memory architecture: short-term memory (recent chat, context), long-term memory (facts about the stream, user preferences), and a memory store (local DB or vector store with embeddings).
- Develop a simple dialogue policy: when to respond, how long to wait for a user to finish speaking, how to address multiple chat points, topic maintenance and topic-switching logic.
- Implement multilingual capability: handle English and French with language detection and safe translation/generation flow.
Why this matters
- The AI needs to produce coherent, context-aware responses and remember relevant details to feel human-like.
How to verify
- Run scripted conversations in a console/test harness and inspect the AI’s ability to remember a user name, follow a topic, and switch topics gracefully.

Subgoal 6: Implement text-to-speech with emotion controls
What to do
- Pick a TTS service or model that supports emotional prosody (tone, pitch, speed) without cloning a real person’s voice.
- Expose parameters for emotion intensity, speaking rate, and volume to influence the avatar’s mouth and facial expressions.
- Normalize and queue audio with precise lip-sync timing to minimize mismatch.
Why this matters
- Voice emotion and pacing drive perceived personality and engagement.
How to verify
- Generate sample phrases with different emotion settings and confirm the avatar’s mouth and expressions respond appropriately.

Subgoal 7: Build social channels integration (Twitch chat, Discord)
What to do
- Create a Twitch bot to read chat, respond when appropriate, and integrate with OBS overlays (e.g., chat panel, viewer count, subs).
- Create a Discord bot that can receive messages, join voice calls, and relay inputs to the AI planner. Decide whether to respond in Discord chat, via the Unity avatar, or both.
- Implement “listen-before-respond” behavior: wait for a user to finish typing/speaking before responding.
- Implement language-aware handling so responses can be in English or French when appropriate.
Why this matters
- Real-time social interaction is core to the streamer experience; robust bots ensure smooth interactions.
How to verify
- Simulate chat messages and Discord inputs; confirm the avatar responds in the planned manner, with no overlapping turns.

Subgoal 8: Connect avatar to live streaming (OBS/Twitch)
What to do
- Create a workflow to render Unity output to OBS (via a window capture or a dedicated streaming pipeline).
- Set up an overlay or scene that shows the avatar, chat, and basic stream metrics.
- Implement a simple timer/trigger: e.g., increase a timer by 3 seconds per sub in a way that’s compliant with Twitch rules and UI clarity.
- Ensure lip-sync audio is captured in stream audio and synchronized with the avatar’s mouth.
Why this matters
- The end-user experience on stream depends on syncing visuals with audio and chat-driven events.
How to verify
- A test stream or local OBS scene to verify capture, lip-sync, and subtitle/overlay cues.

Subgoal 9: Localization and language behavior
What to do
- Implement English and French language flows: detection, generation, and fallback if translation fails.
- Ensure UI and prompts are bilingual where appropriate (including prompts to the audience and avatar responses).
Why this matters
- Multilingual capability expands audience reach and improves engagement with French-speaking viewers.
How to verify
- Run test conversations in both languages and verify correct language use and no cross-language leakage.

Subgoal 10: Data persistence, learning, and memory
What to do
- Persist short-term and long-term memory (names, preferences, recurring topics) across sessions, while respecting privacy and data storage policies.
- Create a simple learning loop: after streams, summarize key interactions and update memory with user preferences and recurring topics.
- Add a reset or privacy mode to clear memory if needed.
Why this matters
- A robust memory system makes interactions feel more natural and personalized.
How to verify
- Simulate multiple sessions and verify memory persists across restarts (where intended) and can be cleared.

Subgoal 11: Project structure, packaging, and documentation
What to do
- Create a Git repository with a clear README, contribution guidelines, and an outline of the project scope.
- Include a detailed README/tutorial with:
  - How to set up Unity, required SDKs, and plugins
  - How to run the MVP locally
  - How to configure the AI model API keys and endpoints
  - How to run the Twitch and Discord bots
  - How to build and stream through OBS
  - Safety and ethics notes (no impersonation of real people, consent for data)
- Add a “CONTRIBUTING” guide and a basic test plan.
Why this matters
