Step-by-step subgoals and reasoning

1) Clarify scope, constraints, and success criteria
- Subgoals:
  - Confirm target Unity LTS version (e.g., the latest LTS at project start) and target platforms (Windows, macOS).
  - Define non-functional goals: latency budget, streaming uptime, maintainability, cost constraints for AI models and TTS.
  - Decide which features are MVP vs. nice-to-have (e.g., MVP includes Twitch chat interaction, lip-sync, basic emotion animation; extras include Minecraft integration and full Discord voice integration).
  - Set success criteria for visuals (facial blend shapes, visemes), for AI (multi-language support, memory), and for integration (Twitch/Discord/OBS work flow).
- Why this matters: A clear scope prevents feature creep and informs architecture decisions, tooling, and budgets.

2) Design overall architecture and data flow
- Subgoals:
  - Define modular components: Twitch IRC client, Discord client, AI Chat Processor, Memory/Persona, Animation Controller, TTS/ASR, Lip-Sync, Perception module, OBS integration, Debug UI.
  - Establish asynchronous data pipelines: incoming chat/voice/events -> AI state -> output text -> TTS audio -> mouth/body animation -> Twitch chat responses.
  - Decide externalization strategy for AI inference (remote API) and TTS (cloud vs. local), to avoid main-thread freezing.
  - Determine how language switching (English ↔ French) flows through translation, persona adaptation, and output.
- Why this matters: A clean, decoupled architecture makes testing, maintenance, and future extensions (e.g., new feeds or new AI backends) feasible.

3) Create project skeleton, folders, and tooling
- Subgoals:
  - Create Unity project with recommended folder structure: Assets/Scripts, Assets/Models, Assets/Animations, Assets/Audio, Assets/Prefabs, Packages, etc.
  - Set up Addressables, the new Input System, and a sample Animator Controller structure (blend trees for visemes and expressions).
  - Prepare a “live debug” UI canvas for state, chat feed, emotional state, and event counters.
  - Add version control defaults (e.g., .gitignore for Unity, package-locks) and a minimal README INSTRUCTIONS.txt template.
- Why this matters: A clean starting point reduces integration friction and makes collaboration smoother.

4) Build the AI persona and memory subsystem
- Subgoals:
  - Define the persona: funny, silly, mischievous, with a focus on teaching life lessons; bilingual English/French capable and context-switching.
  - Design memory: short-term chat context, long-term viewer/history log, topic tracking, and “memory tokens” used to influence responses.
  - Create a lightweight dialogue loop: collect user input (chat/text, voice), feed to AI processor, generate response text, decide emotion/tonality, and trigger appropriate animation and TTS.
  - Plan for language handling: detection, routing to English or French, optional translation steps, and language-specific prosody in TTS.
- Why this matters: The personality and memory drive the character’s believability and interaction quality. Proper memory management and language handling are critical for a coherent experience.

5) Implement AI integration strategy (inference, memory, and planning)
- Subgoals:
  - Decide on the AI backbone: a GPT-5-nano equivalent or a lightweight API-based model; ensure asynchronous, non-blocking calls.
  - Build an AI Chat Processor interface: input context, topic tracking, user history, persona constraints; output response text, mood/intent hints, and potential action commands (e.g., “play anecdote,” “switch language”).
  - Implement an external AI inference pipeline: run model inference in a separate process or server, expose a REST/WebSocket API, and call it from Unity with async HTTP.
  - Add a “planning” step: given the AI output, determine sequence for text response, mouth animation, and any nonverbal cues.
- Why this matters: Non-blocking, external AI prevents Unity frame drops and allows scalable AI workloads. A clear interface keeps the Unity side clean.

6) Flesh out the facial animation and lip-sync system
- Subgoals:
  - Design viseme mapping: map phoneme data or TTS prosody to facial blend shapes (mouth shapes, jaw, lips) and eye behavior (blink, gaze).
  - Integrate a mouth-sync pipeline: real-time mouth movement driven by generated speech text (phoneme timing from TTS or a viseme model).
  - Implement facial expressions: blend trees or animation layers for happiness, sadness, anger, confusion, excitement, etc., driven by AI mood/intent signals.
  - Ensure real-time animation uses animation controllers with blend trees (visemes + emotions) to produce natural movement.
- Why this matters: Realistic talking and expressive reactions are essential for immersion.

7) Implement TTS and speech recognition, with latency handling
- Subgoals:
  - Choose TTS solution (cloud or local) with multilingual and emotional prosody support (English and French; expressiveness).
  - Implement ASR (speech-to-text) for Discord voice and potential live spoken input, if desired, or rely on chat-only input for simplicity.
  - Ensure asynchronous TTS playback and non-blocking audio scheduling in Unity.
  - Sync speech output with lip-sync and mouth visemes in real time.
- Why this matters: Lifelike voice and lip-sync are core to the streaming experience.

8) Integrate Twitch and Discord communications
- Subgoals:
  - Implement Twitch IRC client (e.g., TwitchLib) for chat listening and ability to respond in chat.
  - Implement Twitch event handling (follows, subs, cheers) to trigger OBS timer increments and avatar/voice reactions.
  - Implement Discord integration (text and optional voice). For voice: use a suitable library to listen to channel audio; for text: parse messages and feed into AI.
  - Build proper async message handling: incoming messages processed without blocking main thread; rate limits and throttling respected.
  - Implement a feedback loop: when a new follower/subscriber occurs, add 3 seconds to an OBS timer overlay, and vocalize acknowledgement with appropriate emotion.
- Why this matters: The live interaction with viewers is what makes the project feel authentic.

9) Perception, perception-integration, and Minecraft topic
