- Why this matters: Debug visibility accelerates development and helps with live testing.

12) Code quality, testing, and configurability
- Subgoals:
  - Apply clean, modular coding practices: SOLID-ish structure, clear interfaces, async all the things where appropriate.
  - Document API surface: each module exposes a small set of public methods; add XML doc comments.
  - Create configuration files for API keys, language preferences, and streaming behavior (with secure handling in .gitignore).
  - Build a test plan: unit tests for non-Unity core logic (where feasible) and integration tests for async pipelines.
- Why this matters: Production-readiness hinges on clean code, reliable async behavior, and good docs.

13) Documentation and onboarding
- Subgoals:
  - Produce detailed README/INSTRUCTIONS.txt with setup steps, Twitch/Discord API key setup, language switching, OBS timer setup, and extension points.
  - Provide configuration examples, sample assets, and a minimal “how to extend personality” guide.
- Why this matters: Enables other developers to pick up and extend the project quickly.

14) Security, privacy, and compliance considerations
- Subgoals:
  - Manage tokens securely (use UnitySecureKeyStore or encrypted local storage; avoid hard-coding tokens).
  - Respect Twitch/Discord terms of service; implement rate limiting and user data minimization.
  - Provide a brief privacy note and data retention policy (especially if you store chat history for memory).
- Why this matters: Keeps the project compliant and lowers risk.

Phased plan and deliverables (milestones)

Phase 0 — Foundation and planning (2–4 weeks)
- Deliverables:
  - Project skeleton with folder structure and README template.
  - Basic Unity scene with a placeholder humanoid character and a debug UI panel.
  - Dev ready: Addressables configured, Input System wired, sample Animator Controller scaffold.
