Phase 1 — Character pipeline and lip-sync groundwork (4–8 weeks)
- Deliverables:
  - 3D humanoid asset placeholder (or basic rigged model) with facial rig or blend shapes.
  - Viseme mapping framework and mouth-sync pipeline scaffold.
  - Basic emotion animation controllers (happiness, sadness, anger, curiosity).
- Milestones:
  - Real-time mouth movement driven by generated speech (even with placeholder TTS).

Phase 2 — AI persona, memory, and language handling (6–10 weeks)
- Deliverables:
  - AI Chat Processor interface and a stub implementation connected to a remote language model (GPT-5-nano or equivalent).
  - Memory system architecture (short-term context, long-term viewer memory).
  - Language routing: English and French support, with a translation or bilingual pipeline as needed.
- Milestones:
  - AI can produce a text response within latency targets; memory state updates for subsequent interactions.

Phase 3 — Twitch and Discord integration (6–12 weeks)
- Deliverables:
  - Twitch IRC client wired (listen and respond in chat; send messages back).
  - Twitch events (follows/subs) feed into the OBS timer logic and AI responses.
  - Discord integration (text channel) wired; optional voice input handling if scope allows.
- Milestones:
  - End-to-end loop: chat message received -> AI response -> response posted to Twitch chat.

Phase 4 — Perception, Minecraft, and contextual commentary (8–12 weeks)
- Deliverables:
  - Screen-perception module feeding contextual data to AI.
  - Minecraft observation module (basic event/commentary integration).
  - AI uses perception data to make contextual remarks.
- Milestones:
  - Contextual streams of commentary based on observed events.

Phase 5 — Audio, lip-sync, and emotion-driven animation polish (6–10 weeks)
- Deliverables:
  - TTS integration with multilingual, emotional prosody.
  - Real-time lip-sync synchronized with speech.
  - Fine-tuned animation blending for fluid facial/body expressions matching emotion.
- Milestones:
  - Consistent, natural mouth movement and expression alignment with spoken content.

Phase 6 — OBS integration, debugging UI, and testing (4–6 weeks)
- Deliverables:
  - OBS timer integration; scripts to increment timer with follower/sub events.
  - Robust debug UI panels for live monitoring.
  - End-to-end test plan and test cases; performance profiling results.
- Milestones:
  - Stable streaming pipeline with visible overlay changes and debug telemetry.

Phase 7 — Packaging, docs, and deployment (2–4 weeks)
- Deliverables:
  - Final README/INSTRUCTIONS.txt with setup steps, API key configuration, language switching, and extension tips.
  - Build scripts and platform-specific notes for Windows and Mac.
- Milestones:
  - Production-ready project with clear build instructions.

High-level architecture and data flow (conceptual)

- Input layer:
  - TwitchChatListener (Twitch IRC) and DiscordListener feed messages to AI Processor.
  - Optional: perception module captures screen/game context (Minecraft events, overlay data).

- AI Processing layer:
  - AIChatProcessor calls external AI inference (remote API) asynchronously; returns responseText, mood hints, and actions.
  - MemoryManager stores and retrieves context (viewer topics, history), supports long-term memory.

- Language and voice layer:
  - LanguageRouter routes to English or French, with optional translation steps.
  - TTS module renders speech from responseText with emotion cues; ASR if voice input is used.

- Animation layer:
  - LipSyncController maps visemes from speech to mouth blend shapes.
  - ExpressionController blends facial expressions based on AI mood/intent and dialogue context.
  - AnimatorController orchestrates visemes, eye movement, and body poses.

- Output layer:
  - Speech plays in Unity audio system; mouth/body animation updates in real time.
  - TwitchChatSender sends responses back to Twitch chat.
  - OBS timer updater responds to follower/sub events.

- Perception feedback loop:
  - PerceptionModule provides contextual cues to AI (what’s on screen, game state, chat sentiment) to influence responses.

- Debug UI:
  - Live panels show AI state, last input, last output, current emotion, latency stats.

Key technical considerations and choices you’ll need to document

- AI inference:
  - Use a remote API for AI inference to keep Unity responsive. Ensure proper async handling (HttpClient with await, timeouts, retries, backoff).
  - Model choice: GPT-5-nano or equivalent lightweight model; prepare for API endpoints, authentication, and cost management.

- Speech and lip-sync:
  - Viseme data source: if TTS provides phoneme timing, map to visemes; if not, use a phoneme-to-viseme estimator.
  - Real-time constraints: target sub-second lip-sync latency; account for TTS start-to-audio delay.

- Language handling:
  - English/French bilingual support; decide if you’ll translate on-the-fly or generate bilingual outputs directly, based on model capability and latency.

- Networking:
  - Use asynchronous sockets or high-level libraries for TwitchLib (IRC) and Discord (Discord.Net or equivalent).
  - Ensure thread-safety for Unity objects accessed by async callbacks.

- Asset and performance management:
  - Use Addressables for dynamic assets; keep model/animation assets modular.
  - Maintain a lean runtime footprint, with off-main-thread AI and audio processing where possible.

- OBS integration:
  - Use OBS WebSocket for timer overlay updates; define a small protocol for requesting timer increments.

- Security and privacy:
  - Manage tokens securely; avoid hard-coding credentials; provide a secure config system.

- Testing and QA:
  - Plan for end-to-end testing with simulated chat and events if live Twitch/Discord access isn’t available during development.
  - Include unit tests for non-Unity logic where feasible.

