- Documented run/build steps.

Phase 1: AI streamer character creation and animation pipeline
Subgoals
- Character model and rigging
  - Source or create a humanoid, anime-style model (young adult female) with full facial rig (blendshapes) and/or bone rigging for expressive animation.
  - Ensure facial rig supports visemes (mouth shapes) and eye expressions; include eyebrow and eyelid controls.
  - Import into Unity; set up materials, shading, and a neutral pose.
- Animation assets
  - Create or import blend-tree driven facial expressions (happy, sad, angry, confused, excited, surprised, neutral).
  - Create eye movement cycles (attention, gaze tracking, blinking).
  - Set up a baseline full-body animation repertoire (idle, pose, subtle gestures) to reflect emotion.
- Lip-sync and viseme integration
  - Build a viseme-driven mouth animation pipeline (blend shapes or bone-driven) tied to speech output.
  - Prepare an Animation Rig (humanoid) with a mouth mouth-closed/open trigger and blend-weights for visemes.
- Runtime animation controller
  - Create an Animator Controller with layers for head/face (visemes), eyes, and body postures. Use blend trees for visemes and expressions.
  - Expose parameters: MouthOpen, Viseme0..VisemeN, EyeBlink, Smile, EyebrowRaise, HeadTilt, etc.
- Placeholder pronunciation test
  - Validate lip-sync and facial expressions with sample audio clips to verify timing and synchronization.

Deliverables
- Fully rigged character in Unity with viseme-capable mouth and eye expressions.
- Working Animator Controller with viseme-driven mouth movement and expression-driven body/face layers.

Phase 2: AI backend architecture and memory
Subgoals
- AI engine design
  - Decide on an external inference approach (GPT-5-nano or equivalent) and an API wrapper.
  - Define memory model: short-term memory (recent chat), long-term memory (viewer topics, recurring themes), and persona constraints.
  - Multilingual support: English and French; plan translation steps when switching languages.
- Conversation flow
  - Build an AI conversation pipeline: input (chat, voice, events) -> memory -> language model -> output text -> TTS and actions.
  - Implement a simple intent/emotion mapping to drive animation state changes.
- Language switching
  - Implement real-time language selection and changeover without losing context; potentially add a translation layer if needed.
- Voice and emotions
  - Plan for text-to-speech (TTS) with emotional prosody (tone, rate, pitch) and optional prerecorded voice cues.
  - Map TTS output to lip-sync data (visemes) and to emotion-driven animations.

Deliverables
- Modular AI pipeline: AIChatProcessor, MemoryManager, LanguageAdapter, EmotionModel.
- API wrappers for GPT-5-nano (or equivalent) with async calls and error handling.
- Translation/ bilingual support hook.

Phase 3: Multimodal input/output and synchronization
Subgoals
- Speech recognition and TTS
  - Integrate a speech recognition module (ASR) for mouth/playback in real-time (optional if you rely on text input; recommended for live voice interactions).
  - Integrate a TTS solution with adjustable prosody; ensure produced audio can be played back in Unity and synchronized with mouth/viseme animation.
- Real-time lip-sync pipeline
  - Build a pipeline that takes TTS phoneme or viseme data and animates the mouth accordingly, with natural pauses.
  - Ensure synchronization between audio playback and animation. Handle audio latency gracefully.
- Emotion-driven animation controller
  - Extend the Animator with an Emotion state that drives facial expressions and body posture. Tie this to AI outputs (mood, admiration, humour, mischief, etc.).
- Async networking for streaming
  - All Twitch/Discord API interactions must be async without blocking the main thread. Use async/await patterns and Unity's synchronization context to marshal UI updates to the main thread.
- Debug UI
  - Create runtime panels: AI State, Current Input, Latest Response, Emotion State, Chat Queue, and Connection status.

Deliverables
- A synchronized lip-sync pipeline driven by TTS output with viseme data.
- Async, robust input listeners for chat and voice with no frame drops.

Phase 4: Twitch and Discord integration
Subgoals
- Twitch IRC client
  - Implement a Twitch IRC client (e.g., using TwitchLib or raw sockets) to join channels, read chat, and listen to follow/sub/cheer events.
  - Implement OAuth authentication, token refresh logic, and secure storage of tokens.
- Twitch event handling
  - Parse and handle events: new follower, new subscriber, chat messages, raids, cheers.
  - Implement “every new follower/sub adds 3 seconds to an OBS timer overlay” behavior: expose a configurable timer increment function.
  - Respond to chat messages with natural-language responses generated by the AI, including language switching when necessary.
- Discord integration
  - Implement Discord voice and text integration (Discord.Net/DSharpPlus). The AI can join voice calls and respond to text chat, listening and replying after user finishes speaking.
- OBS/overlay integration
  - Create a mechanism to expose a timer value to the OBS scene via a simple protocol (e.g., WebSocket/UDP or local file/socket) so that overlay displays can update in near real time.
  - Ensure the AI can trigger overlay changes in response to events.
- Language and localization tests
  - Validate bilingual behavior in both chat and audio outputs during Twitch/Discord interactions.

Deliverables
- Working Twitch IRC client with authentication, chat reading, and event handling.
- Discord bot/voice integration that can join channels and receive/send messages.
- OBS timer update mechanism hooked to follower/sub events.

Phase 5: Minecraft integration and multi-modal perception
Subgoals
- Minecraft avatar/AI interaction (advanced)
  - Provide a high-level plan for how the AI could observe or control a Minecraft client (e.g., via a modded interface or API) and comment on gameplay.
  - If implementing, create a modular wrapper to interface with Minecraft (e.g., through a protocol like RCON or a mod that exposes a REST/WebSocket API).
- Screen/game perception
  - Implement screen capture (video frame) or game window capture as a perception input into the AI.
  - Process frames (low-lidelity) to extract contextual cues (e.g., in-game events, on-screen chat overlays) to influence responses.
- Narrative integration
  - Create an “in-game commentary” mode where the AI mentions Minecraft topics and viewer questions in real time.

Deliverables
- Optional Minecraft perception/controller module with clear integration points.

Phase 6: System architecture, performance, and deployment
Subgoals
- Decouple systems
  - Ensure clear data flow boundaries: UI/UX layer, animation layer, AI layer, IO layer (Twitch/Discord), and perception layer.
  - Use interfaces and dependency injection where possible to enable testing and replacement of components.
- Performance and threading
  - All network I/O runs on background threads or async tasks; UI/Unity updates are dispatched to the main thread.
  - Use Unity’s Job System or Task-based patterns if appropriate; avoid blocking main thread.
- Localization and language switching
  - Implement a language manager that can switch languages at runtime, preserving conversation context where possible.
- Observability and debugging
  - Implement in-scene debug panels showing: current mood, last user input, last AI output, queue length, and connection status.
  - Implement a lightweight log viewer that can be toggled on/off.
- Security and compliance
  - Store API keys securely (not in source code); recommend using Unity’s PlayerPrefs with encryption or a secure key store for builds.
  - Be mindful of Twitch/Discord API terms and rate limits; design for graceful degradation.

Deliverables
- A modular, scalable runtime with clear boundaries and good performance characteristics.

Phase 7: Testing, MVP, and user documentation
Subgoals
- Build a minimal viable product (MVP)
  - MVP focuses on: a visible AI streamer character, basic lip-sync, simple but robust Twitch chat interaction, and a working OBS timer response to new followers/subs.
  - Use English as default and French bilingual support for a subset of flows to validate bilingual switching.
- End-to-end testing
  - Simulate Twitch chat inputs and verify responses, latency, and lip-sync behavior.
  - Verify speech output timing and mouth movements align with spoken content.
  - Validate Discord integration with a test server/channel.
- Documentation
  - Documentation in README/INSTRUCTIONS.txt for project setup, keys, languages, and extension points.
  - Provide examples of config files, how to trigger the OBS timer, how to switch languages live.

Deliverables
- MVP running scenario with documented setup steps.
- Test plans and results.

Phase 8: Extras and future-proofing
Subgoals
- Memory and learning
  - Outline how the AI could improve responses over time based on conversation history. Include a plan for privacy/compliance considerations.
- Personalization tuning
  - Expose personality controls (tone, humor level, mischief factor) to adjust the AI’s persona dynamically.
- Observability
  - Expand the debug UI to include more metrics, such as latency, memory usage, and AI response times.
- Extendability
  - Provide clear extension points for new languages, new input channels, or new surface areas (e.g., another chat platform).

Deliverables
- A documented extension plan and ready-to-extend codebase.

MVP and deliverables checklist (recommended order)
- MVP build:
  - Unity project with the 3D anime-style character, facial and eye animations, and viseme-driven lip-sync pipeline.
  - Twitch chat integration, basic follower/sub acknowledgment with 3-second timer increments, and AI-generated responses.
  - TTS output with synchronized mouth movements and emotion-driven animations.
  - Basic Discord integration (text chat listening; optional voice role as a future step).
  - OBS timer overlay interface hook (or a simple in-scene timer that can be mirrored to OBS).
- Debug UI and basic monitoring panels.
- Documentation: INSTRUCTIONS.txt with run/build/setup and how to extend.

Recommended concrete architecture (high level)
- Unity components
  - AIStreamerController: orchestrates behaviors, language, and AI-driven actions.
  - TwitchClient (OAuthAuthenticator, TwitchIRCClient, TwitchEventListener): handles Twitch login, chat, and events.
  - DiscordClient: handles Discord text/voice interactions.
  - MemoryManager: stores short-term memory (recent chat, user topics) and long-term patterns.
  - ConversationEngine: sends prompts to GPT-5-nano or equivalent, receives responses, formats for UI and TTS.
  - EmotionController: maps AI sentiment to animation parameters (face, body).
  - LipSyncManager: handles viseme data to drive mouth animations in sync with TTS.
  - SpeechPipeline: TTS output, phoneme/viseme mapping, audio playback.
  - PerceptionModule: screen/game capture and processing for contextual inputs.
  - OBSInterface: timer synchronization with OBS overlay (if applicable).
  - DebugUI: panels for state, messages, and emotion triggers.
- Data flow
  - Input: Twitch chat / Discord text / voice input / perception.
  - Processing: MemoryManager + ConversationEngine + EmotionController.
  - Output: AI text response -> SpeechPipeline (TTS) -> LipSyncManager + Animator Controller -> Visuals.
  - Side effects: Twitch chat back-replies, Discord responses, OBS timer increments, and notification events.

Key technical considerations and limitations
- Real-time inference with GPT-5-nano
  - Expect latency depending on API, rate limits, and model size. Design a queuing system with timeouts; implement fallback to cached responses if needed.
- Lip-sync fidelity
  - If viseme data isn’t exposed by the TTS service, approximate using phoneme parsing from output text or a precomputed phoneme table tied to speech rate and prosody.
- Language switching
  - Maintain persona and memory across languages; consider per-language memories if needed to ensure coherence.
- Async integration
  - Ensure all Twitch/Discord I/O, AI inference, memory updates, and perception data processing run asynchronously from the Unity main thread; marshal UI updates to the main thread.
- Security and API keys
  - Do not hard-code keys. Use secure storage and recommended practices for token refresh.

What to put in the INSTRUCTIONS.txt (content outline)
- How to open and run the Unity project
- Required software versions (Unity LTS version, platform SDKs)
- How to configure Twitch and Discord API keys (OAuth scopes, token retrieval, token refresh)
- How to set up OBS timer overlays and trigger events
- How to switch languages live and test bilingual flows
- How to extend the AI’s personality and behavior (adjusting memory, emotion weights, and humor level)
- How to extend or replace the AI model (switch to another model if needed)
- How to build for Windows and Mac, and any platform-specific caveats
- How to run the debug UI and interpret outputs
- Directory structure references and code entry points

Notes and pragmatic guidance
- Start with a minimal, robust MVP first: core character visuals, basic lip-sync, Twitch chat read/write, and a simple AI response loop. Then layer in Discord, perception, and advanced emotion dynamics.
- Keep the code modular with clear interfaces. This makes it easier to swap out AI backends or input channels later.
- Build a small test harness for Twitch chat inputs and a simulated AI response loop to validate timing and behavior before connecting real services.
- Be mindful of licensing for AI models and TTS voices. Ensure terms of service allow streaming usage and text-to-speech for a public-facing avatar.

If you want, I can turn this into a detailed, phase-by-phase project plan with explicit task lists, estimated durations, and a minimal viable product (MVP) checklist you can drop into a project management tool.
