Phase-by-phase plan (concise runbook)
- Phase 1: Setup and MVP skeleton
  - Create project structure, placeholder avatar, and core scripts scaffolding.
  - Validate Twitch IRC connection with a test message printout.
  - Build a basic AI response loop (offline) to ensure UI updates correctly.
- Phase 2: AI capable loop
  - Integrate the AI chat processor with an external API (GPT-5-nano or equivalent) and memory.
  - Implement TTS and lip-sync bridge; connect to AnimationController.
- Phase 3: Avatar and animation polish
  - Implement viseme-to-blendshape mapping; add a few expressive facial/body animations.
- Phase 4: Language and memory features
  - Add English/French switching in AI outputs and tutorial prompts; wrap memory to remember past topics.
- Phase 5: Twitch and Discord integration
  - Finish Twitch chat and event handling; add Discord integration if time permits.
- Phase 6: Perception, Minecraft, and multi-modal
  - Add PerceptionModule hooks and MinecraftObserver; test with simulated data.
- Phase 7: Debug UI and observability
  - Complete the DebugUI panel, log streams, and metrics.
- Phase 8: OBS integration and build
  - Implement timer increments and build for Windows/macOS; verify OBS capture workflow.

Practical considerations and tradeoffs
- Performance: Run heavy AI in a separate worker thread or external service to avoid Unity frame drops. Use a queue system and marshal results back to the main thread.
- Latency: Expect some latency due to API calls; implement clever buffering, streaming of short prompts, and pre-warmed prompts to reduce user-visible delay.
- Security: Store API keys in secure locations (environment variables, Unity PlayerPrefs with encryption, or a server proxy). Do not hard-code keys in scripts.
- Extensibility: Keep interfaces stable; add new languages, new perception modules, or new streaming services as separate components without touching core AI loop.
- Compliance and privacy: Consider viewer data retention rules and data processing policies; provide a user-facing privacy note in INSTRUCTIONS.txt.

What you’ll likely deliver at MVP
- A clean Unity project with the required folder structure and a basic character.
- Twitch chat reading and a simple AI-driven response with lip-sync and initial facial/body animation.
- A debug UI panel showing AI state and recent messages.
- A working outline for memory, language switching, and a pathway to add Discord/Twitch event handling.
- README/INSTRUCTIONS.txt with setup steps for Twitch/Discord keys and how to run, extend, and build.

