Subgoal 8: Real-time control loop, data flow, and threading model
What you’ll do
- Create a robust, asynchronous pipeline:
  1) Receive chat/events (Twitch/Discord)
  2) Feed to AI Chat Processor (contextualize, memory)
  3) Generate response text via external API
  4) Synthesize speech (with TTS)
  5) Animate avatar (mouth, eyes, body)
  6) Send chat responses back to Twitch via IRC and log to Discord if needed
- Implement a main “AIController” that coordinates these steps while ensuring thread-safety and main-thread updates for Unity objects.
Deliverables
- AIController.cs orchestrating the end-to-end loop with careful thread synchronization.
- A message queue and a dispatcher to marshal data to Unity’s main thread.
Key decisions
- Use asynchronous Task-based methods for I/O; run heavy AI inference and network calls on worker threads.
- Ensure Unity updates (Blend Trees, Animator parameters) are performed on the main thread.

Subgoal 9: Debug UI, telemetry, and state monitoring
What you’ll do
- Build a debug UI panel to show:
  - Current emotion/state
  - Last few viewer messages
  - AI response text
  - Lip-sync or mouth shape weights
  - Streaming event counters (e.g., follower/sub increments)
Deliverables
- DebugUIController with panels, toggles, and live readouts.
Key decisions
- Include a minimal log viewer to help diagnose timing and latency issues.
- Provide a “pause AI” toggle for safe debugging in the editor.

Subgoal 10: Language switching, multilingual behavior
What you’ll do
- Implement LanguageSwitcher to switch between English and French in real-time, both for understanding input and generating output.
- Ensure TTS voice changes or voice mode for different languages if needed.
Deliverables
- LanguageSwitcher.cs with a seamless bilingual mode switching mechanism.
Key decisions
- Decide whether TTS voice should be language-specific (same voice with multilingual support vs different voice models).

Subgoal 11: OBS integration and streaming overlay triggers
What you’ll do
- Implement OBS-related hooks to adjust an on-screen timer overlay when new followers/subscribers occur (add 3 seconds per event).
- Create a simple OBS-compatible data source hook or a shared file/UDP/WS message to communicate timer increments as an overlay widget.
Deliverables
- OBSController.cs with API calls or UDP messages for timer increments.
Key decisions
- Ensure the trigger logic is purely data-driven to avoid desyncs with actual Twitch events.

Subgoal 12: Audio pipeline and streaming compatibility
What you’ll do
- Ensure audio playback for TTS is synchronized with mouth animations.
- Enable streaming through OBS by rendering the Unity window and/or streaming the application process.
- Confirm cross-platform compatibility (Windows/macOS) and provide build settings for both.
Deliverables
- Working audio playback pipeline and a basic OBS integration note.
Key decisions
- If streaming from a single Unity window, document the recommended workflow (OBS Window Capture or Game Capture).

Subgoal 13: Documentation, configuration, and deployment plan
What you’ll do
- Prepare INSTRUCTIONS.txt with:
  - How to open and run the Unity project
  - How to set up Twitch and Discord API keys
  - How to extend/modify AI persona
  - How to trigger OBS timer increments
  - How to switch languages in real time
- Include example configuration files (config.json, twitch_config.json, discord_config.json) with placeholder values.
Deliverables
- INSTRUCTIONS.txt and example config files.
Key decisions
- Include security considerations for tokens (environment variables or secure storage) rather than hard-coding keys.

Subgoal 14: MVP release plan and incremental milestones
What you’ll do
- Define a minimal viable product (MVP) that demonstrates:
  - Live Twitch chat read
  - Simple AI response with English/French switching
  - Lip-sync-driven mouth animation
  - Basic facial expressions
  - Observable debug UI
- Plan additional features in subsequent iterations (Minecraft observer, advanced perception, richer persona, Discord voice, etc.).
Deliverables
- Milestone plan with dates and acceptance criteria.
Key decisions
- Start with Twitch chat only (no Discord) for MVP if needed to reduce complexity; add Discord in a second iteration.

Subgoal 15: Project-wide coding standards and best practices
What you’ll do
- Enforce clean, modular code with:
  - Proper async/await usage
  - Clear interfaces between systems (AI layer, animation layer, I/O layer)
  - Comprehensive comments and XML docs
  - Unit and integration tests where feasible (Unity Test Framework)
- Ensure code is well-commented and easy to extend (e.g., new languages, new behaviors).
Deliverables
- Code conventions document, sample interfaces, and a basic test plan.

Suggested script/files outline with responsibilities (Assets/Scripts)
- OAuthAuthenticator.cs
  - Handles Twitch login/token retrieval; stores tokens securely
- TwitchIRCClient.cs
  - Connects to Twitch IRC, subscribes to chat, parses messages
- TwitchEventListener.cs
  - Listens to follows/subs/raids; triggers OBS timer and animations
- DiscordIntegration.cs
  - Optional: linking to text/voice channels; message/voice events to AI
- AIChatProcessor.cs
  - Contextualizes input (chat, events), passes prompts to language model API; handles memory references
- MemoryManager.cs
  - Maintains persistent and session memory for continuity
- LanguageSwitcher.cs
  - Manages English/French state and language-specific prompts
- TTSManager.cs
  - Async text-to-speech generation; returns audio clip or PCM stream
- SpeechSynthesisSync.cs
  - Real-time alignment of audio with mouth visemes
- VisemeMapper.cs
  - Maps phonemes to viseme/viseme-weights
- AnimationController.cs
  - Animator bridge to drive facial and body animations based on visemes and emotion
- EmotionState.cs
  - Data model for current emotion, intensity, and transitions
- MinecraftObserver.cs
  - Interfaces for Minecraft player actions and commentary hooks
- PerceptionModule.cs
  - Screen capture or scene understanding hooks for contextual commentary
- OBSController.cs
  - Signals to OBS (overlay timer) or via a simple data bridge
- DebugUIController.cs
  - In-editor/debug UI panels for status, messages, and emotion
- ConfigManager.cs
  - Global config, API keys loading, environment settings
- NetworkClient.cs
  - Generic async socket management for low-level TCP/UDP if needed
- ScriptExecutionOrder markers (if necessary) to ensure proper startup sequence

Phase-by-phase plan (concise runbook)
- Phase 1: Setup and MVP skeleton
  - Create project structure, placeholder avatar, and core scripts scaffolding.
  - Validate Twitch IRC connection with a test message printout.
  - Build a basic AI response loop (offline) to ensure UI updates correctly.
- Phase 2: AI capable loop
  - Integrate the AI chat processor with an external API (GPT-5-nano or equivalent) and memory.
  - Implement TTS and lip-sync bridge; connect to AnimationController.
- Phase 3: Avatar and animation polish
  - Implement viseme-to-blendshape mapping; add a few expressive facial/body animations.
- Phase 4: Language and memory features
  - Add English/French switching in AI outputs and tutorial prompts; wrap memory to remember past topics.
- Phase 5: Twitch and Discord integration
  - Finish Twitch chat and event handling; add Discord integration if time permits.
- Phase 6: Perception, Minecraft, and multi-modal
  - Add PerceptionModule hooks and MinecraftObserver; test with simulated data.
- Phase 7: Debug UI and observability
  - Complete the DebugUI panel, log streams, and metrics.
- Phase 8: OBS integration and build
  - Implement timer increments and build for Windows/macOS; verify OBS capture workflow.

Practical considerations and tradeoffs
- Performance: Run heavy AI in a separate worker thread or external service to avoid Unity frame drops. Use a queue system and marshal results back to the main thread.
- Latency: Expect some latency due to API calls; implement clever buffering, streaming of short prompts, and pre-warmed prompts to reduce user-visible delay.
- Security: Store API keys in secure locations (environment variables, Unity PlayerPrefs with encryption, or a server proxy). Do not hard-code keys in scripts.
- Extensibility: Keep interfaces stable; add new languages, new perception modules, or new streaming services as separate components without touching core AI loop.
- Compliance and privacy: Consider viewer data retention rules and data processing policies; provide a user-facing privacy note in INSTRUCTIONS.txt.

What you’ll likely deliver at MVP
- A clean Unity project with the required folder structure and a basic character.
- Twitch chat reading and a simple AI-driven response with lip-sync and initial facial/body animation.
- A debug UI panel showing AI state and recent messages.
- A working outline for memory, language switching, and a pathway to add Discord/Twitch event handling.
- README/INSTRUCTIONS.txt with setup steps for Twitch/Discord keys and how to run, extend, and build.

If you’d like, I can now translate this plan into concrete file templates and skeleton code for the core scripts (e.g., a minimal but functional version of OAuthAuthenticator, TwitchIRCClient, AIChatProcessor, TTSManager, and AnimationController) to jump-start the implementation. I can also provide a lightweight data flow diagram in text to illustrate how data moves through the system.
