    - $19 tier: unlimited AI-generated quizzes
- Content policy
  - Content should be original or properly licensed. You can seed with templates and outlines, then let authors or AI generate original content that you curate.
- Set measurable outcomes
  - Student dashboards show lessons completed, exercises completed, quizzes completed
  - Points system: 1 point per quiz completed
  - Leaderboards: “most exercises done” and “most quizzes done”
- Define success criteria
  - Functional: user auth, class/subject navigation, lesson delivery, quizzes with AI correction, billing integration, dashboards, and leaderboards
  - Nonfunctional: security, performance, scalability, accessibility, responsive UI

2) Define user roles and user journeys (subgoals)
- Roles
  - Student: views classes, lessons, exercises, quizzes; tracks progress; earns points; sees leaderboard
  - Teacher/Admin: creates content, manages users, monitors progress, configures quizzes
  - Billing/Support: handles subscriptions, renewals, cancellations, refunds
- Primary user journeys
  - Onboarding: sign up → choose class/term → select subject → start lessons
  - Lesson flow: view content → attempt exercises → take quizzes → get AI-corrected feedback → see progress
  - Billing flow: select plan → enter payment → access unlock → manage subscription
  - Leaderboard flow: watch ranking pages updated in real-time/daily
  - Progress dashboard: view stats (quizzes done, exercises done, points, recent activity)

3) Choose tech stack and high-level architecture (subgoals)
- Frontend
  - HTML/CSS/JS with a modern framework (e.g., React) or a simpler SPA approach
  - Responsive design, accessible components, design system
- Backend
  - Python-based server (FastAPI preferred for modern async APIs)
  - ORM: SQLAlchemy
  - Database: PostgreSQL (recommended) or SQLite for dev
- AI and content
  - LLM provider: OpenAI API (GPT-4 or similar) or another compliant LLM
  - Use AI for: generating quiz content, grading/correction for MCQ/structured answers, suggesting explanations
- Billing and payments
  - Stripe for subscriptions, plan management, and webhooks
- Deployment and hosting
  - Frontend: static hosting (Vercel/Netlify)
  - Backend: containerized API (Docker) on a cloud provider (AWS/GCP/Azure)
  - CI/CD pipeline for tests, migrations, and deployments
- Security and compliance
  - JWT-based authentication, role-based access control
  - Data protection, encryption in transit and at rest, regular security reviews

4) Data model and schemas (subgoals)
- Core entities and relationships (high level)
  - User: id, email, password_hash, name, role (student/teacher/admin), region, created_at
  - Class/Term: id, name (e.g., Première Terminale - 2024-2025), start_date, end_date
  - Subject: id, name (French, Math, ...), color/icon for UI
  - Lesson: id, subject_id, class_id, unit_number, lesson_number, title, objectives, content_html, video_url, reading_materials
  - Exercise: id, lesson_id, prompt, type (multiple_choice, short_text, code, etc.), correct_answer, difficulty
  - Quiz: id, lesson_id, title, num_questions, time_limit, generated_by_ai boolean
  - QuizQuestion: id, quiz_id, prompt, options (JSON), correct_option
  - QuizAttempt: id, user_id, quiz_id, score, completed_at, passed boolean
  - ExerciseAttempt: id, user_id, exercise_id, result (correct/incorrect), attempted_at
  - Points: id, user_id, quiz_points (1 per quiz), exercise_points (count), total_points
  - BillingPlan: id, name, price_cents, features (JSON), max_quizzes (for the lower tier), unlimited_quizzes flag
  - Subscription: id, user_id, plan_id, status, start_date, end_date, stripe_subscription_id
  - Payment: id, user_id, amount_cents, currency, status, timestamp, stripe_charge_id
  - LeaderboardSnapshot: id, timestamp, ranking_type (exercises, quizzes), data (JSON)
- Example SQLAlchemy model snippets (simplified)
  - class User(Base): __tablename__ = 'users'; id = Column(Integer, primary_key=True); email = Column(String, unique=True)
  - class Subject(Base): __tablename__ = 'subjects'; id = Column(Integer, primary_key=True); name = Column(String)
  - class Lesson(Base): __tablename__ = 'lessons'; id = Column(Integer, primary_key=True); subject_id = Column(Integer, ForeignKey('subjects.id'))
  - class Quiz(Base): __tablename__ = 'quizzes'; id = Column(Integer, primary_key=True); lesson_id = Column(Integer, ForeignKey('lessons.id'))
  - class QuizQuestion(Base): __tablename__ = 'quiz_questions'; id = Column(Integer, primary_key=True); quiz_id = Column(Integer, ForeignKey('quizzes.id'))
- Notes
  - Use JSON/Text fields where flexible data is needed (e.g., exercise prompts, quiz options)
  - Normalize for relations (one-to-many: lesson -> questions, quiz -> questions)
  - Add audit fields (created_at, updated_at) to most tables
  - Ensure proper indexing on frequently queried fields (user_id, lesson_id, quiz_id)

5) Content strategy and lesson templates (subgoals)
- Lesson structure (template you can reuse for every subject)
  - Unit/Module label, Lesson number, Title
  - Objectives (learning outcomes, measurable)
  - Theory/Concepts section (rich text)
  - Worked examples (step-by-step)
  - Guided practice (short activities)
  - Exercises (prompt, expected answer types, difficulty)
  - Quiz setup (linked to this lesson): number of questions, type
  - Additional resources: readings, videos, external links
  - Assessment: rubric or scoring notes
- Content creation approach
  - Build an authoring UI for teachers to create/edit lessons and exercises
  - Seed with original, templated content for first units to illustrate (not copied from external sites)
  - Create robust templates to allow AI-generated content to be plugged in and then curated
- Example starter skeletons (original content)
  - French (Terminale) – Unit 1: Expression écrite et compréhension
    - Lesson 1: Compréhension orale et vocabulaire
    - Lesson 2: Analyse de texte littéraire (court extrait)
  - Math – Unit 1: Functions and scaling
    - Lesson 1: Linear functions
    - Lesson 2: Quadratic functions
  - And similarly for other subjects
- Content quality controls
  - Human review for factual accuracy and alignment with curriculum
  - Accessibility checks (alt text, semantic headings, readable language)

6) AI integration for quizzes and corrections (subgoals)
- Quiz generation (AI)
  - Prompt design: generate N questions of specified type for a given lesson
  - Ensure variety: mix of MCQ, short answer, and applied problems
  - Include correct answers and explainers
- AI-based correction
  - MCQ grading is automatic
  - For open-ended/short-answer questions, use AI to compare student answer with model answer
  - Provide a rationale explanation generated by AI
- Safety and reliability
  - Include a human-in-the-loop flag for uncertain results
  - Provide transparency: show score, correct answers, and a short explanation
- Rate limits and cost controls
  - Cache AI results where possible
  - Define daily quotas per user to manage API usage

7) Billing, plans, and subscriptions (subgoals)
- Plan definitions
  - Basic (Pulse): $9/month
    - Access: lessons, limited quizzes per month, standard corrections
  - Pro (Unlimited Quizzes): $19/month
    - Access: unlimited AI-generated quizzes, enhanced analytics, no limit on quizzes
- Implementation details
  - Integrate Stripe for recurring subscriptions
  - Webhooks to sync subscription status to the app
  - Access control tied to active subscription
- Data handling for billing
  - Store minimal necessary payment data (Stripe IDs) and status
  - Audit logs for subscription changes, billing events

8) Gamification and leaderboards (subgoals)
- Metrics and scoring
  - Points: 1 point per quiz completed (as you stated)
  - Exercise count: tracked per user
- Leaderboard design
  - Two leaderboards: 
    - Most exercises completed (all-time or time-bounded)
    - Most quizzes completed
  - Optional regional/class-based rankings
- Data freshness
  - Recompute rankings on a schedule (e.g., every 10 minutes) or event-driven when quiz/exercise is submitted
- UI considerations
  - Leaderboard views with filters (time range, subject, class)
  - Profile pages showing individual stats and progress toward next rank

9) API design and endpoints (subgoals)
- Authentication and users
  - POST /auth/register, POST /auth/login, POST /auth/refresh
  - GET /me, GET /users/{id} (admin)
- Class, subjects, and content
  - GET /classes, GET /classes/{id}/subjects
  - GET /subjects/{id}/lessons, GET /lessons/{id}
  - POST /lessons (teacher), PUT /lessons/{id}, DELETE /lessons/{id}
- Exercises and quizzes
  - GET /lessons/{id}/exercises
  - POST /exercises/attempts, GET /exercises/{id}/attempts
  - POST /quizzes, GET /quizzes/{id}, POST /quizzes/{id}/attempts
  - POST /quizzes/{id}/generate (AI-driven generation)
- Quiz correction and feedback
  - POST /quizzes/{quiz_id}/submit with user answers
  - Back-end uses AI to validate open-ended responses and returns score and feedback
- Progress and dashboards
  - GET /dashboard (user stats)
  - GET /leaderboard?type=quizzes|exercises&period=all|week
- Billing
  - POST /billing/subscribe, POST /billing/webhook
  - GET /billing/plans, GET /billing/subscription
- Admin and content management
  - Admin-only: user management, content approval, content stats

10) Frontend design and UI/UX (subgoals)
- Design system
  - Consistent typography, color palette, iconography
  - Components: Navbar, Card, LessonCard, QuizCard, ExerciseCard, ProgressRing, LeaderboardTable, Modal
- Navigation and flows
  - Clear paths: Home → Class → Subject → Lesson → Activities
  - Persistent progress indicators and quick access to ongoing modules
- Accessibility
  - Keyboard navigable, screen-reader friendly, proper semantic markup
- Visual inspiration
  - Study-oriented UI with clean typography, readable content blocks
  - “SchoolMouv-like” clean layout but with your own branding and original content
- Responsiveness
  - Desktop and mobile layouts with touch-friendly controls

11) Content creation plan for Terminale/Première (practical approach)
- Create a content authoring workflow
  - Admin/teachers use an editor to create lessons, add objectives, theory content, examples, exercises, and quiz prompts
  - Use templates so new lessons can be created quickly
  - AI-assisted generation for quizzes and explanations, followed by human curation
- Seed content strategy
  - Start with a well-structured set of units for each subject (e.g., 4–6 units per subject per term)
  - Build 1–2 representative lessons per unit to demonstrate structure
  - Gradually expand content with author contributions and AI-generated drafts that are curated
- Content governance
  - Review process for accuracy, alignment to curriculum, and pedagogy
  - Versioning of lessons for updates

12) Non-functional requirements and quality plan (subgoals)
- Performance
  - Efficient queries with proper indexing
  - Caching of frequently accessed static content
- Security
  - JWT with short expiry, refresh tokens
  - Role-based access control
  - Secure handling of payments and PII
- Reliability
  - Health checks, automated tests, minimal downtime
  - Backups for the database
- observability
  - Logging, metrics, and dashboards for errors, latency, and user activity
- Compliance
  - Data privacy considerations (especially if minors are involved; consider consent, data minimization)

13) Milestones and implementation plan (phased)
- Phase 0: Discovery and design (2–3 weeks)
  - Finalize requirements, user journeys, and high-level architecture
  - Create initial data models and API contract
- Phase 1: Core platform skeleton (4–6 weeks)
  - Implement auth, user roles, class/subject structure
  - Build lesson content delivery and exercise/quizzes scaffolding
  - Integrate simple quiz submission and grading (MCQ)
- Phase 2: AI-powered quizzes and corrections (4–5 weeks)
  - Integrate AI for quiz generation and correction
  - Add feedback and explanations
- Phase 3: Billing, subscriptions, and dashboards (3–4 weeks)
  - Stripe integration, plans, and webhooks
  - Student dashboard with progress and GPA-like metrics
- Phase 4: Leaderboards and analytics (2–3 weeks)
  - Implement two leaderboards and ranking updates
- Phase 5: Content authoring tools and expansion (ongoing)
  - Build full lesson authoring UI, templates, content review workflow
- Phase 6: UI polish, accessibility, and QA (2–3 weeks)
  - UI/UX refinements, accessibility checks, end-to-end testing
- Phase 7: Deployment, monitoring, and launch
  - Deploy to production, set up monitoring, and plan for support

14) Example initial content skeleton (original, non-copyrighted)
- Subject: French (Terminale) – Unit 1
  - Lesson 1: Expression écrite – Objectifs
    - Objectives: Write a structured essay; use transition words; demonstrate argumentation
    - Theory: Quick guide to thesis statements, intro/conclusion, paragraph structure
    - Worked example: Short sample argument with annotated parts
    - Exercises: 
      - Exercise 1: Identify thesis statements in sample texts
      - Exercise 2: Write a 150-180 word paragraph on a given prompt
    - Quiz:
      - Q1: Which sentence is a strong thesis?
      - Q2: Which transition best connects idea A to idea B?
      - AI-generated correction: Provide feedback and suggested improvements
- Subject: Math – Unit 1
  - Lesson 1: Linear Functions
    - Objectives: Understand slope, intercept form, graph of ax + b
    - Theory: Derivation of slope from two points; graphing basics
    - Worked example: Solve and graph y = 2x + 3
    - Exercises: 
      - Solve for y given x and slope
      - Graph several lines with different slopes
    - Quiz: MCQ about slope-intercept form; basic graph interpretation

Note: The above are templates and examples to illustrate structure. You should populate all lessons with original content or licensed material and maintain curriculum alignment.

15) Next steps and deliverables
