- Deliverables: a short requirements list and a checklist (e.g., must-have sections: hero, about, features, contact; accessibility score, responsive behavior).
- Acceptance criteria: clear list of sections, responsive behavior described, accessibility expectations defined.

2) design concept and information architecture
- What you’ll do: sketch a rough layout (wireframe) and decide on semantic structure.
- Why it’s needed: informs HTML semantics and CSS layout; improves accessibility and SEO.
- Deliverables: sitemap (header, main sections, footer) and a simple wireframe or layout notes (e.g., hero at top, 3 feature cards, testimonials).
- Acceptance criteria: taxonomy of sections mapped to semantic HTML elements (header, nav, main, section, aside, footer).

3) asset and style plan
- What you’ll do: choose a color palette, typography, and define design tokens (colors, font sizes, spacing).
- Why it’s needed: ensures visual consistency and easier maintenance.
- Deliverables: color and font palette, a small CSS variables plan (e.g., --primary, --bg, --text, --radius).
- Acceptance criteria: documented tokens; plan aligns with responsive design.

4) project skeleton and tooling
- What you’ll do: create the project folder structure and basic files.
- Why it’s needed: provides a clean starting point and repeatable workflow.
- Deliverables: index.html, css/styles.css, optional assets/ folder, README.md.
- Acceptance criteria: boilerplate HTML/CSS ready; meta viewport tag included; eslint/prettier or a simple style guide can be added later.

5) implement header and navigation (accessibility-first)
- What you’ll do: build a semantic header with a nav element, logo area, and accessible links; ensure keyboard operability.
- Why it’s needed: core site chrome; first interaction point.
- Deliverables: header markup, basic CSS for layout, responsive nav behavior (horizontal on wide screens, stack or collapsible on small screens if desired).
- Acceptance criteria: aria-labels where appropriate; proper focus order; semantic elements used.

6) build hero section
- What you’ll do: create a prominent hero with a heading, supporting text, and a call-to-action.
- Why it’s needed: sets the tone and encourages engagement.
- Deliverables: hero markup and CSS (background image or gradient, typography, CTA button).
- Acceptance criteria: visually prominent, accessible contrast, works on mobile.

7) build content sections (about, features/services, testimonials, etc.)
- What you’ll do: implement additional semantic sections with content blocks (cards, grids).
- Why it’s needed: delivers core message and information.
- Deliverables: sections like about, features (3-4 cards), testimonials (optional), and a secondary CTA.
- Acceptance criteria: consistent spacing, responsive grid, accessible images/text.

8) build footer and utility elements
- What you’ll do: add a footer with contact info, links, and social icons; optional newsletter form.
- Why it’s needed: provides completing information and navigation.
- Deliverables: footer markup and CSS.
- Acceptance criteria: accessible form (if added), correct landmark order.

9) responsive and accessible design
- What you’ll do: implement responsive layout using CSS grid/flexbox; add media queries; ensure accessible color contrast and semantics.
- Why it’s needed: works on all devices and accessible to users with disabilities.
- Deliverables: at least 2–3 breakpoints; fluid typography; semantic headings and landmarks.
- Acceptance criteria: passes basic accessibility checks (semantic tags, alt text, keyboard navigation).

10) performance and best practices
- What you’ll do: optimize assets, minify CSS, avoid render-blocking resources where possible.
- Why it’s needed: fast user experience; better SEO.
- Deliverables: optimized images (if used), clean CSS, small bundle.
- Acceptance criteria: reasonable page weight, no blocking CSS/JS for a static page (if no JS is used).

11) testing and iteration
- What you’ll do: test across devices/browsers (Chrome/Edge/Firefox/Safari), test accessibility basics, and fix issues.
- Why it’s needed: ensures a robust, predictable experience.
- Deliverables: small test checklist and a list of fixes.
- Acceptance criteria: layout stays consistent across viewports; no broken links; accessible structure.

12) finalize and document
- What you’ll do: create a README with how to run, how to extend, and design decisions.
- Why it’s needed: helps future maintenance.
- Deliverables: README.md, a clean codebase.
- Acceptance criteria: clear instructions; comments in code where necessary.

