Section 1: Step-by-step reasoning and subgoals (with rationale and outputs)

1) Define success criteria and project scope
- What it aims to achieve: Establish clear, measurable goals so the home page is built to meet real needs and you can validate success after launch.
- Key decisions to make:
  - Who is the primary audience (developers, business buyers, end users, researchers)?
  - What is the primary action you want visitors to take (start a chat, request a demo, sign up, view features)?
  - What metrics will indicate success (conversion rate for CTA, time to first interaction, bounce rate, demo requests, signups)?
- Outputs:
  - A success criteria document (KPIs, target metrics, acceptance criteria).
  - A clearly bounded scope (what’s in-scope vs. out-of-scope for this page).

2) Stakeholder alignment and requirements gathering
- What it aims to achieve: Align on constraints, expectations, and priorities across teams (marketing, product, design, engineering, legal).
- Key decisions to make:
  - Branding constraints (logo usage, color system, typography).
  - Legal/compliance needs (privacy disclosures, data handling notes, accessibility standards).
  - Hosting and tech constraints (frameworks, hosting environment, CMS if any).
- Outputs:
  - Requirements document or a backlog: features, content needs, integrations, and non-functional requirements.
  - Decision log capturing trade-offs (e.g., richer interactivity vs. performance).

3) Define audience, user journeys, and content strategy
- What it aims to achieve: Understand user needs and map the path visitors take to accomplish goals on the page.
- Key decisions to make:
  - Primary user personas (e.g., AI architect, product manager, developer).
  - Core user journeys (e.g., “learn about agent → see demo → start trial”).
  - Content priorities: hero messaging, feature highlights, testimonials, demo area, pricing or sign-up CTAs.
- Outputs:
  - Personas and user journeys (storyboards or narrative scenarios).
  - Content outline or sitemap for the site.
  - Copy deck (hero headline, subhead, CTAs, feature blurbs, microcopy).

4) Information architecture and site structure
- What it aims to achieve: Create a navigable, scannable structure that supports the intended user journeys.
- Key decisions to make:
  - Which pages/components belong on the home page vs. separate pages (e.g., full Features page, Docs, Pricing).
  - Navigation labels and hierarchy.
- Outputs:
  - Sitemap (high-level pages and sections).
  - Wireframes or low-fidelity layout sketches for the home page.

5) UI/UX design system and visual direction
- What it aims to achieve: Ensure a cohesive, accessible, and scalable visual language that aligns with the brand.
- Key decisions to make:
  - Brand identity: color palette, typography, iconography, imagery style.
  - UI components needed (hero, feature cards, tabbed/demo area, CTA buttons, nav, footer, forms).
  - Accessibility targets (contrast ratios, keyboard navigation, ARIA roles).
- Outputs:
  - Design system or component library outline (tokens, components, expected states).
  - High-fidelity mockups or a design prototype for the home page.

6) Plan interactivity and the AI agent demo
- What it aims to achieve: Provide a compelling, low-friction way for visitors to experience the AI agent.
- Key decisions to make:
  - Type of demo: inline chat widget, a guided interactive playground, or a “demo transcript” showcase.
  - Data handling within the demo (what prompts are used, how responses are shown, privacy notices).
  - Performance expectations (latency, loading indicators, fallbacks if the agent is unavailable).
- Outputs:
  - Interaction design specs (UI flows, states, error handling).
  - Demo content plan (sample prompts, example conversations).
  - Privacy/disclaimer copy for the demo.

7) Technical architecture and implementation approach
- What it aims to achieve: Choose an appropriate tech stack and deployment approach that balances speed, maintainability, and extensibility.
