[2025-10-11 13:25:07] [INFO] 📋 Planning based on prompt: Build a fully functional Roadmap Editor similar to the one used on roadmap.sh
, but limited to local use only.

Technologies allowed: strictly HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and optionally a small Python backend for local file saving.

Goal: users can create and edit interactive roadmaps with the same connection logic, metadata, and node system as roadmap.sh.

Required features:

Nodes: draggable, editable blocks that support 4-way connections (top, bottom, left, right).

Each node has metadata: title, description, color, status (e.g. “planned”, “in-progress”, “done”).

Connections: arrows/lines linking nodes. Lines should auto-update when nodes move.

Toolbar:

“New Roadmap” → clears the workspace

“Save Roadmap” → saves to localStorage or via small Python backend

“Open Saved Roadmap” → reloads previous roadmap

Editor canvas: zoom and pan support.

No frameworks, no libraries, no npm. Pure vanilla JS, CSS, HTML (and optional small Python for save/load).

Keep code in just a few files:

index.html (structure + toolbar)

style.css (layout + styling)

main.js (logic for nodes, connections, save/load)

(optional) server.py (simple local save API if needed).

Expected behavior:

Users can drag and connect nodes freely, edit text inline, and the roadmap structure updates visually in real-time.

Users can save and later reopen their roadmaps.

Design is minimalist but functional, mirroring roadmap.sh’s node-link editor style.

Deliverables: fully working local web app, compact and readable code, no dependencies.
