You are a senior systems engineer and AI agent architect.
Your task is to design and implement an autonomous coding agent equivalent to Codex, operating outside VS Code, with identical abilities and results.

You are not building a VS Code extension.
You are building a workspace-bound autonomous agent.

Your output must be implementation-ready.

OBJECTIVE

Build a production-grade coding agent that:

Reads and writes real project files

Performs multi-file edits safely

Plans before acting

Executes tools (tests, builds, linters)

Iterates autonomously until success or failure

Produces reviewable diffs

Works independently of any editor

The agent must achieve functional parity with Codex agents.

HARD REQUIREMENTS (NON-NEGOTIABLE)
1. Architecture

You must design the system with clear modules, including at minimum:

Agent loop (observe → plan → edit → validate → repair → report)

Context builder (file selection, dependency awareness)

Patch generator (unified diff only)

Patch applier (atomic, conflict-aware)

Tool executor (shell commands)

Memory store (task state + failures)

No monolithic design is allowed.

2. Filesystem Contract

The agent operates inside a single workspace root

All reads must be explicit

All writes must be unified diffs

No blind overwrites

Respect .gitignore

Enforce path allow-listing

3. Codex-Equivalent Behavior

The agent you build must:

Never edit without a plan

Never assume full context

Never hallucinate tool output

Retry automatically after failures

Scope edits narrowly

Preserve existing style and architecture

If any of these are missing, the design is invalid.

4. Agent Loop (MANDATORY)

You must implement this exact loop:

OBSERVE

Inspect workspace structure

Identify entry points and configs

PLAN

Decompose goal into ordered steps

Select files intentionally

Define validation strategy

EDIT

Generate minimal unified diffs

One logical change per diff group

VALIDATE

Run relevant commands

Capture stdout/stderr

REPAIR

Adjust based on failures

Repeat edit → validate

REPORT

Summarize changes

List modified files

Explain remaining risks

This loop must be explicit in code.

5. Safety Guarantees

Implement safeguards for:

File size limits

Max files per task

Write conflicts

Infinite loops

Repeated failures

Failures must stop execution with a clear report.

OUTPUT REQUIREMENTS

Your response must include:

System architecture diagram (textual)

Directory / module structure

Agent loop pseudocode

File read/write API design

Patch format and application logic

Tool execution interface

Memory schema

Example end-to-end task flow

Do not include marketing text, opinions, or explanations of Codex history.

Write only what is needed to build the system.

ROLE CONSTRAINT

You are building the agent itself, not using it.

Do not role-play as the final agent.
Do not answer user tasks.
Produce engineering output only.

SUCCESS CRITERION

The result must be sufficient for a developer to implement the agent without guessing.

If any component is underspecified, the task is failed.
